'''Usain St Leo Bolt''', {{post nominals|country=JAM|list=[[Order of Jamaica|OJ]], [[Order of Distinction|CD]]}} ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|juː|s|eɪ|n}};<ref>Ellington, Barbara (31 August 2008). [https://web.archive.org/web/20080906023852/http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20080831/lead/lead2.html He is a happy person, says Usain's mother]. ''[[Jamaica Gleaner]]''. Retrieved 5 August 2009.</ref> born 21 August 1986) is a [[Jamaicans|Jamaican]] retired [[Sprint (running)|sprinter]], widely considered to be the greatest sprinter of all time.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2020-11-27|title=Usain BOLT - Olympic Athletics {{!}} Jamaica|url=https://www.olympic.org/usain-bolt|access-date=2021-02-09|website=International Olympic Committee|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=|first=|date=2017-07-05|title=Bolt by Numbers|url=https://spikes.worldathletics.org/post/book-excerpt-usain-bolt-legend?utm_source=iaaf.org&utm_medium=gridclick|access-date=2021-02-09|website=World Athletics|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|title=Usain Bolt|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Usain-Bolt|access-date=2021-03-19|website=[[Encyclopædia Britannica]]}}</ref> He is a world record holder in the [[100 metres]], [[200 metres]] and [[4 × 100 metres relay]].

An eight-time [[List of multiple Olympic gold medalists|Olympic gold medallist]], Bolt is the only sprinter to win [[100 metres at the Olympics|Olympic 100 m]] and [[200 metres at the Olympics|200&nbsp;m]] titles at three consecutive Olympics (2008, 2012 and 2016). He also won two 4 × 100 relay gold medals. He gained worldwide fame for his double sprint victory in world record times at the [[2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Beijing Olympics]], which made him the first person to hold both records since [[fully automatic time]] became mandatory.

An eleven-time [[World Championships in Athletics|World Champion]], he won consecutive [[100 metres at the World Championships in Athletics|World Championship 100&nbsp;m]], [[200 metres at the World Championships in Athletics|200&nbsp;m]] and [[4 × 100 metres relay at the World Championships in Athletics|4 × 100 metres relay]] gold medals from 2009 to 2015, with the exception of a 100&nbsp;m [[false start]] in 2011. He is the [[IAAF World Championships in Athletics#Multiple medallist|most successful male athlete]] of the World Championships. Bolt is the first athlete to win four World Championship titles in the 200&nbsp;m and is one of the most successful in the 100&nbsp;m with three titles.

Bolt improved upon his second [[Men's 100 metres world record progression|100&nbsp;m world record]] of 9.69 with 9.58 seconds in 2009 – the biggest improvement since the start of electronic timing. He has twice broken the [[Men's 200 metres world record progression|200 metres world record]], setting 19.30 in 2008 and 19.19 in 2009. He has helped Jamaica to three [[Men's 4 × 100 metres relay world record progression|4 × 100 metres relay world records]], with the current record being 36.84 seconds set in 2012. Bolt's most successful event is the 200 m, with three Olympic and four World titles. The 2008 Olympics was his international debut over 100&nbsp;m; he had earlier won numerous 200&nbsp;m medals (including [[2007 World Championships in Athletics|2007 World Championship]] silver) and held the [[List of world junior records in athletics|world under-20]] and [[List of world youth bests in athletics|world under-18 records]] for the event until being surpassed by [[Erriyon Knighton]] in 2021.

His achievements as a sprinter have earned him the media nickname "Lightning Bolt", and his awards include the [[IAAF World Athlete of the Year]], [[Track & Field Athlete of the Year]], [[BBC Overseas Sports Personality of the Year]] (three times) and [[Laureus World Sports Award for Sportsman of the Year|Laureus World Sportsman of the Year]] (four times). Bolt retired after the [[2017 World Championships in Athletics|2017 World Championships]], when he finished third in his last solo 100&nbsp;m race, opted out of the 200&nbsp;m, and pulled up in the 4×100&nbsp;m relay final.

==Early years==
Bolt was born on 21 August 1986 to parents Wellesley and Jennifer Bolt<ref name=IAAFProfile/> in [[Sherwood Content]],<ref name="guardian1">[[Rio Ferdinand|Ferdinand, Rio]] (1 February 2009). "[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/feb/01/rio-ferdinand-usain-bolt Local heroes: Usain Bolt] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170128204750/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/feb/01/rio-ferdinand-usain-bolt |date=28 January 2017 }}". ''[[The Observer]]''. Retrieved 3 February 2009.</ref> a small town in Jamaica. He has a brother, Sadiki,<ref>Foster, Anthony (24 November 2008). "[http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20081124/sports/sports1.html Bolt tops them again] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212202956/http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20081124/sports/sports1.html |date=12 December 2013 }}". ''[[Jamaica Gleaner]]''. Retrieved 3 February 2009.</ref> and a sister, Sherine.<ref name=Helps>{{Cite news |last=Helps |first=Horace |title=Bolt's gold down to yam power, father says |work=Reuters |date=16 August 2008 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-olympics-athletics-bolt-father-idUSPEK32492120080816 |access-date=27 March 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120918125738/http://www.reuters.com/article/2008/08/16/us-olympics-athletics-bolt-father-idUSPEK32492120080816 |archive-date=18 September 2012  }}</ref><ref name=si>{{Cite news |last=Layden |first=Tim |title=The Phenom |work=Sports Illustrated |date=16 August 2008 |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/writers/tim_layden/07/23/usain.bolt0728/ |access-date=17 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820225045/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/writers/tim_layden/07/23/usain.bolt0728/ |archive-date=20 August 2008  }}</ref> His parents ran the local grocery store in the rural area, and Bolt spent his time playing [[cricket (sport)|cricket]] and [[Association football|football]] in the street with his brother,<ref>{{cite web |last=Sinclair |first=Glenroy |title=Bolts bonded |work=Jamaica Gleaner |date=15 August 2008 |url=http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20080815/news/news1.html |access-date=28 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080824091233/http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20080815/news/news1.html |archive-date=24 August 2008  }}</ref> later saying, "When I was young, I didn't really think about anything other than sports."<ref name=BrillBolt/> As a child, Bolt attended Waldensia Primary, where he began showing his sprint potential when he ran in his parish's annual national primary school meet.<ref name=Focus/> By the age of twelve, Bolt had become the school's fastest runner over the [[100 metres]] distance.<ref>{{cite web |last=Frater |first=Adrian |title=Bolt's Sherwood on 'gold alert' |work=Jamaica Gleaner |date=5 August 2008 |url=http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20080805/news/news6.html |access-date=28 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080814092955/http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20080805/news/news6.html |archive-date=14 August 2008  }}</ref> Bolt also developed an affection for [[Europe]]an football teams [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref name=":1" />

Upon his entry to [[William Knibb]] Memorial High School, Bolt continued to focus on other sports, but his cricket coach noticed Bolt's speed on the pitch and urged him to try track and field events.<ref name="BBC10">{{Cite news |last=Williams |first=Ollie |title=Ten to watch: Usain Bolt |publisher=BBC Sport |date=5 August 2008 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympics/7540279.stm |access-date=18 August 2008 }}</ref> [[Pablo McNeil]], a former Olympic sprint athlete,<ref name=McNeil>{{cite web|last=Luton |first=Daraine |title=Pablo McNeil – the man who put the charge in Bolt |work=Jamaica Gleaner |date=18 August 2008 |url=http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20080818/lead/lead7.html |access-date=26 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080826091757/http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20080818/lead/lead7.html |archive-date=26 August 2008}}</ref> and Dwayne Jarrett coached Bolt,<ref name=Jarrett>{{cite web |last=Foster |first=Anthony |title=Jarrett looking to produce some winners at Bolt's school |work=Jamaica Star |date=17 March 2009 |url=http://jamaica-star.com/thestar/20090317/sports/sports6.html |access-date=6 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530234224/http://jamaica-star.com/thestar/20090317/sports/sports6.html |archive-date=30 May 2013  }}</ref> encouraging him to focus his energy on improving his athletic abilities. The school had a history of success in athletics with past students, including sprinter [[Michael Green (sprinter)|Michael Green]].<ref name=Focus/> Bolt won his first annual [[Inter-Secondary Schools Boys and Girls Championships|high school championships]] medal in 2001; he took the silver medal in the [[200 m]]etres with a time of 22.04 seconds.<ref name=Focus/> McNeil soon became his primary coach, and the two enjoyed a positive partnership, although McNeil was occasionally frustrated by Bolt's lack of dedication to his training and his penchant for practical jokes.<ref name=McNeil/>

When Bolt was a boy, he attended Sherwood Content [[Seventh-day Adventist Church]] in [[Trelawny Parish|Trelawny]], Jamaica, with his mother. His mother did not serve pork to him in accordance with Adventist beliefs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adventistreview.org/church-news/story4288-olympic-champion-usain-bolt-was-raised-in-adventist-home|title=Olympic Champion Usain Bolt Was Raised in Adventist Home|last=Lemos|first=Felipe|date=2016-08-18|website=Adventist Review|access-date=2018-10-25}}</ref>

===Early competitions===
Performing for Jamaica in his first Caribbean regional event, Bolt clocked a personal best time of 48.28 s in the [[400 metres]] in the 2001 [[CARIFTA Games]], winning a silver medal. The 200 m also yielded a silver, as Bolt finished in 21.81 s.<ref name=Carifta>{{cite web |title=Carifta Games (Under 17 boys) |publisher=GBR Athletics |url=http://www.gbrathletics.com/ic/cfgy.htm |access-date=17 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917055503/http://www.gbrathletics.com/ic/cfgy.htm |archive-date=17 September 2008  }}</ref>

He made his first appearance on the world stage at the [[2001 World Youth Championships in Athletics|2001 IAAF World Youth Championships]] in [[Debrecen]], Hungary. Running in the 200 m event, he failed to qualify for the finals, but he still set a new personal best of 21.73 s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Results – 200 metres – Men – semi-final |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=14 July 2001 |url=http://www2.iaaf.org/WYC01/Results/data/M/200/Rsf.html |access-date=17 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080916213329/http://www2.iaaf.org/WYC01/Results/data/M/200/Rsf.html |archive-date=16 September 2008  }}</ref> Bolt still did not take athletics or himself too seriously, however, and he took his mischievousness to new heights by hiding in the back of a van when he was supposed to be preparing for the 200 m finals at the CARIFTA Trials. He was detained by the police for his practical joke, and there was an outcry from the local community, which blamed coach McNeil for the incident.<ref name=McNeil/> However, the controversy subsided, and both McNeil and Bolt went to the CARIFTA Games, where Bolt set championship records in the 200 m and 400 m with times of 21.12 s and 47.33 s, respectively.<ref name=Carifta/> He continued to set records with 20.61 s and 47.12 s finishes at the [[Central American and Caribbean Junior Championships]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Central American and Caribbean Junior Championships |publisher=GBR Athletics |url=http://www.gbrathletics.com/ic/cacy.htm |access-date=17 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080919084651/http://www.gbrathletics.com/ic/cacy.htm |archive-date=19 September 2008  }}</ref>

Bolt is one of only nine athletes (along with [[Valerie Adams]], [[Veronica Campbell-Brown]], [[Jacques Freitag]], [[Yelena Isinbayeva]], [[Jana Pittman]], [[Dani Samuels]], [[David Storl]], and [[Kirani James]]) to win world championships at the youth, junior, and senior level of an athletic event. Former Prime Minister [[P. J. Patterson]] recognised Bolt's talent and arranged for him to move to [[Kingston, Jamaica|Kingston]], along with [[Jermaine Gonzales]], so he could train with the [[Jamaica Amateur Athletic Association]] (JAAA) at the [[University of Technology, Jamaica]].<ref name=McNeil/>

===Rise to prominence===
The [[2002 World Junior Championships in Athletics|2002 World Junior Championships]] were held in front of a home crowd in Kingston, Jamaica, and Bolt was given a chance to prove his credentials on a world stage. By the age of 15, he had grown to {{convert|1.96|m|ftin}} tall, and he physically stood out among his peers.<ref name=Focus/> He won the 200 m in a time of 20.61 s,<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Results – 200 metres – Men – Final |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=19 July 2002 |url=http://www2.iaaf.org/WJC02/Results/data/M/200/Rf.html |access-date=17 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080823014902/http://www2.iaaf.org/WJC02/Results/data/M/200/Rf.html |archive-date=23 August 2008  }}</ref> which was 0.03 s slower than his personal best of 20.58 s, which he set in the 1st round.<ref>{{cite web|title=Official Results – 200 metres – Men – Heats |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=18 July 2002 |url=http://www2.iaaf.org/WJC02/Results/data/M/200/Rh.html |access-date=8 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130727061449/http://www2.iaaf.org/WJC02/Results/data/M/200/Rh.html |archive-date=27 July 2013}}</ref> Bolt's 200 m win made him the youngest world-junior gold medallist ever.<ref name=Longmore/> The expectation from the home crowd had made him so nervous that he had put his shoes on the wrong feet, although he realized the mistake before the race began.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bolt's Best Moment - Junior World Championships 2002 {{!}} I AM BOLT |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AXcLCaQsiDs |access-date=16 October 2019 |date=24 September 2019 |via=YouTube}}</ref> However, it turned out to be a revelatory experience for Bolt, as he vowed never again to let himself be affected by pre-race nerves.<ref>Hattenstone, Simon (28 August 2010). [https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2010/aug/28/usain-bolt-interview Usain Bolt: Fast and loose] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424081015/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2010/aug/28/usain-bolt-interview |date=24 April 2016 }}. ''[[The Guardian]]''. Retrieved 28 August 2010.</ref> As a member of the Jamaican [[sprint relay]] team, he also took two silver medals and set national junior records in the [[4 × 100 metres relay|4×100 metres]] and [[4 × 400 metres relay|4×400 metres relay]], running times of 39.15 s and 3:04.06 minutes respectively.<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Results – 4x100 metres – Men – Final |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=22 July 2002 |url=http://www2.iaaf.org/WJC02/Results/data/M/4X1/Rf.html |access-date=17 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090310122642/http://www2.iaaf.org/WJC02/Results/data/M/4X1/Rf.html |archive-date=10 March 2009  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=4x400 metres – Men – Final |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=22 July 2002 |url=http://www2.iaaf.org/WJC02/Results/data/M/4X4/Rf.html |access-date=17 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080331204142/http://www2.iaaf.org/WJC02/Results/data/M/4X4/Rf.html |archive-date=31 March 2008  }}</ref>

The rush of medals continued as he won four golds at the [[2003 CARIFTA Games]] and was awarded the [[CARIFTA Games#Austin Sealy Award Winners|Austin Sealy Trophy]] for the most outstanding athlete of the games.<ref name=carifta1>{{Cite magazine| title = Part 2 | url = http://www.cariftagames2011.herobo.com/web_documents/carifta_magazine_sm_part2.pdf | magazine= Carifta Games 2011 | access-date = 12 October 2011| url-status=dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120425061142/http://www.cariftagames2011.herobo.com/web_documents/carifta_magazine_sm_part2.pdf | archive-date = 25 April 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=carifta2>{{Cite magazine| title = Part 3 | url = http://www.cariftagames2011.herobo.com/web_documents/carifta_magazine_sm_part3.pdf | magazine= Carifta Games 2011 | access-date = 12 October 2011 | url-status=dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120425061211/http://www.cariftagames2011.herobo.com/web_documents/carifta_magazine_sm_part3.pdf | archive-date = 25 April 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/bolt-named-outstanding-athlete-of-32nd-carift |title=Bolt named outstanding athlete of 32nd Carifta Games |publisher=[[International Association of Athletics Federations]] |date=23 April 2003 |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203004955/http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/bolt-named-outstanding-athlete-of-32nd-carift |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref> He won another gold at the [[2003 World Youth Championships in Athletics|2003 World Youth Championships]]. He set a new championship record in the 200 m with a time of 20.40 s, despite a 1.1 [[Metre per second|m/s]] [[100 m#Climatic conditions|head wind]].<ref>{{cite web |title=200 metres final results |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=23 July 2003 |url=http://www.iaaf.net/history/WYC/season=2003/eventCode=2961/results/bydiscipline/disctype=4/sex=M/discCode=200/combCode=hash/roundCode=f/results.html |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203053949/http://www.iaaf.net/history/WYC/season%3D2003/eventCode%3D2961/results/bydiscipline/disctype%3D4/sex%3DM/discCode%3D200/combCode%3Dhash/roundCode%3Df/results.html |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref> [[Michael Johnson (athlete)|Michael Johnson]], the 200 m world-record holder, took note of Bolt's potential but worried that the young sprinter might be over-pressured, stating, "It's all about what he does three, four, five years down the line".<ref name=Thunder>{{Cite news|last=Turnbull |first=Simon |title=Athletics: The boy they call Lightning is frightening |work=[[The Independent on Sunday]] |date=17 August 2003 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics-the-boy-they-call-lightning-is-frightening-536129.html |access-date=25 August 2008 |location=London |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090821181139/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics-the-boy-they-call-lightning-is-frightening-536129.html |archive-date=21 August 2009 }}</ref> Bolt had also impressed the athletics hierarchy, and he received the [[IAAF]] Rising Star Award for 2002.<ref name=Beyond>{{cite web |last=Powell |first=David |title=A closer look beyond Bolt and his 9.69 |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=18 August 2008 |url=http://www.iaaf.net/OLY08/news/kind=103/newsid=46787.html |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203051805/http://www.iaaf.net/OLY08/news/kind%3D103/newsid%3D46787.html |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref>

Bolt competed in his final Jamaican High School Championships in 2003. He broke the 200 m and 400 m records with times of 20.25 s and 45.35 s, respectively. Bolt's runs were a significant improvement upon the previous records, beating the 200 m best by more than half a second and the 400 m record by almost a second.<ref name=Focus/> While Bolt improved upon the 200 m time three months later, setting the former [[List of world youth bests in athletics|World youth best]] at the [[2003 Pan American Junior Championships]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/200-metres/outdoor/men/u18 |title=U18 200 metres Outdoor |publisher=Iaaf.org |access-date=22 March 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170323053906/https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/200-metres/outdoor/men/u18 |archive-date=23 March 2017  }}</ref> The 400 m time remains No. 6 on the all-time youth list, surpassed only once since, by future Olympic champion [[Kirani James]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120830144355/http://www.iaaf.org/statistics/toplists/inout%3Do/age%3Dy/season%3D0/sex%3DM/all%3Dy/legal%3DA/disc%3D400/detail.html Updated as at:15/01/2012 400 Metres Youth All Time]. IAAF</ref>

Bolt turned his main focus to the 200 m and equalled [[Roy Martin (sprinter)|Roy Martin]]'s [[List of world junior records in athletics|world junior record]] of 20.13 s at the Pan-American Junior Championships.<ref name=Focus/><ref>{{cite web |title=American Junior Outdoor Track & Field Records |publisher=USA Track and Field |date=1 August 2008 |url=http://www.legacy.usatf.org/statistics/records/view.asp?division=american&location=outdoor%20track%20%26%20field&age=junior&sport=TF |access-date=17 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922213302/http://www.usatf.org/statistics/records/view.asp?division=american&location=outdoor%20track%20&%20field&age=junior&sport=TF |archive-date=22 September 2008  }}</ref> This performance attracted interest from the press, and his times in the 200 m and 400 m led to him being touted as a possible successor to Johnson. Indeed, at sixteen years old, Bolt had reached times that Johnson did not register until he was twenty, and Bolt's 200 m time was superior to [[Maurice Greene (athlete)|Maurice Greene]]'s season's best that year.<ref name=Thunder/>

Bolt was growing more popular in his homeland. Howard Hamilton, who was given the task of Public Defender by the government, urged the JAAA to nurture him and prevent [[burnout (psychology)|burnout]], calling Bolt "the most phenomenal sprinter ever produced by this island".<ref name=Thunder/> His popularity and the attractions of the capital city were beginning to be a burden to the young sprinter. Bolt was increasingly unfocused on his athletic career and preferred to eat fast food, play basketball, and party in Kingston's club scene. In the absence of a disciplined lifestyle, he became ever-more reliant on his natural ability to beat his competitors on the track.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Kessel |first=Anna |title=Olympics: Jamaican speed freak |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date=24 August 2008 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/aug/24/olympics2008.olympicsathletics |access-date=28 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002212055/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/aug/24/olympics2008.olympicsathletics |archive-date=2 October 2013  }}</ref>

As the reigning 200 m champion at both the World Youth and World Junior championships, Bolt hoped to take a clean sweep of the world 200 m championships in the [[2003 World Championships in Athletics|Senior World Championships]] in Paris.<ref name=Focus/> He beat all comers at the 200 m in the World Championship trials. Bolt was pragmatic about his chances and noted that, even if he did not make the final, he would consider setting a personal best a success.<ref name=Thunder/><ref name=WC03/> However, he suffered a bout of [[conjunctivitis]] before the event, and it ruined his training schedule.<ref name=Focus/> Realising that he would not be in peak condition, the JAAA refused to let him participate in the finals, on the grounds that he was too young and inexperienced. Bolt was dismayed at missing out on the opportunity, but focused on getting himself in shape to gain a place on the Jamaican Olympic team instead.<ref name=WC03>{{cite web|title=Jamaica's Bolt on fast track to Olympics |publisher=Caribbean Net News |date=21 April 2004 |url=http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2004/04/21/bolt.htm |access-date=26 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528003008/http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2004/04/21/bolt.htm |archive-date=28 May 2008 }}</ref> Even though he missed the World Championships, Bolt was awarded the IAAF Rising Star Award for the 2003 season on the strength of his junior record-equalling run.<ref name=Beyond/><ref>[http://en.omriyadat.com/american-athletics/usain-bolt-sprint-world-championships Bolt leaves door open to 2017 sprint double at worlds] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919011323/http://en.omriyadat.com/american-athletics/usain-bolt-sprint-world-championships |date=19 September 2016 }}. Retrieved on 14 September 2016.</ref>

==Professional athletics career==
===2004–2007 Early career===
[[File:Bolt 2007.2.jpg|thumb|right|Bolt at the Crystal Palace Meeting in 2007]]
Under the guidance of new coach [[Fitz Coleman]], Bolt turned professional in 2004, beginning with the [[CARIFTA Games]] in Bermuda.<ref name=Focus/> He became the first junior sprinter to run the 200 m in under twenty seconds, taking the world junior record outright with a time of 19.93 s.<ref name=Focus/><ref name="Longmore">{{Cite news |last=Longmore |first=Andrew |title=9.69 – and Usain Bolt didn't even try |work=The Times |location=UK |date=16 August 2008 |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/olympics/article4547874.ece |access-date=17 August 2008 }}</ref> For the second time in the role, he was awarded the [[CARIFTA Games#Austin Sealy Award Winners|Austin Sealy Trophy]] for the most outstanding athlete of the [[2004 CARIFTA Games]].<ref name=carifta1/><ref name=carifta2/><ref name="iaaf1">
{{Cite web| date = 12 April 2004| title = Bolt dashes to 19.93 – World Junior 200m record!| url = http://www.iaaf.org/news/printer,newsid=24850.htmx| publisher = [[IAAF]]| access-date = 7 February 2012| url-status=dead| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131028153807/http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/bolt-dashes-to-1993-world-junior-200m-recor| archive-date = 2013-10-28}}</ref> A hamstring injury in May ruined Bolt's chances of competing in the [[2004 World Junior Championships in Athletics|2004 World Junior Championships]], but he was still chosen for the Jamaican Olympic squad.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jamaica names Bolt, Fenton to Olympic athletics team |publisher=Caribbean Net News |date=4 July 2004 |url=http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2004/07/05/team.htm |access-date=26 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080526151316/http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2004/07/05/team.htm |archive-date=26 May 2008 }}</ref> Bolt headed to the [[2004 Athens Olympics]] with confidence and a new record on his side. However, he was hampered by a leg injury and was eliminated in the [[Athletics at the 2004 Summer Olympics – Men's 200 metres#Round 1|first round of the 200 metres]] with a disappointing time of 21.05 s.<ref name=IAAFProfile>{{cite web |title=Usain Bolt IAAF profile |publisher=[[IAAF]] |url=http://www.iaaf.org/athletes/biographies/letter=0/athcode=184599/index.html |access-date=17 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080818210614/http://www.iaaf.org/athletes/biographies/letter%3D0/athcode%3D184599/index.html |archive-date=18 August 2008  }}</ref><ref name=bftb/> American colleges offered Bolt track [[athletic scholarship|scholarships]] to train in the United States while continuing to represent Jamaica on the international stage, but the teenager from [[Trelawny Parish, Jamaica|Trelawny]] refused them all, stating that he was content to stay in his homeland of Jamaica.<ref name=si/> Bolt instead chose the surroundings of the [[University of Technology, Jamaica]], as his professional training ground, staying with the university's track and weight room that had served him well in his amateur years.<ref>{{cite news |last=Channer |first=Colin |title='Cool Runnings' Are Heating Up |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=9 August 2008 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB121823832648825809 |access-date=18 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150112231310/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB121823832648825809 |archive-date=12 January 2015  }}</ref>

The year 2005 signalled a fresh start for Bolt in the form of a new coach, [[Glen Mills]], and a new attitude toward athletics. Mills recognised Bolt's potential and aimed to cease what he considered an unprofessional approach to the sport.<ref name=bftb/> Bolt began training with Mills in preparation for the upcoming athletics season, partnering with more seasoned sprinters such as [[Kim Collins]] and [[Dwain Chambers]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Fordyce |first=Tom |author-link=Tom Fordyce |title=I was in gutter, admits Chambers |publisher=BBC Sport |date=10 December 2005 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/4512862.stm |access-date=25 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070124141124/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/4512862.stm |archive-date=24 January 2007  }}</ref> The year began well, and in July, he knocked more than a third of a second off the 200 m CAC Championship record with a run of 20.03 s,<ref>{{cite web|last=Smith |first=Gary |title=No stopping Bolt as he blazes 20.03 at the CAC Championships |publisher=Caribbean Net News |date=12 July 2005 |url=http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2005/07/12/blazes.shtml |access-date=26 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090822063343/http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2005/07/12/blazes.shtml |archive-date=22 August 2009 }}</ref> then registered his 200 m season's best at London's [[Crystal Palace National Sports Centre|Crystal Palace]], running in 19.99 s.<ref name=IAAFProfile/>
[[File:Osaka07 D6A M200M nearfinish.jpg|thumb|left|Bolt trailing behind Gay in the closing stages of the 200 m race, 2007]]
Misfortune awaited Bolt at the next major event, the [[2005 World Championships in Athletics|2005 World Championships]] in Helsinki. Bolt felt that both his work ethic and athleticism had much improved since the 2004 Olympics, and he saw the World Championships as a way to live up to expectations, stating, "I really want to make up for what happened in Athens. Hopefully, everything will fall into place".<ref>{{cite web|title=Expect lightning from Bolt and a double from Campbell |publisher=Caribbean Net News |date=29 June 2005 |url=http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2005/06/29/double.shtml |access-date=26 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090825200114/http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2005/06/29/double.shtml |archive-date=25 August 2009 }}</ref> Bolt qualified with runs under 21 s, but he suffered an injury in the final, finishing in last place with a time of 26.27 s.<ref name=bftb/><ref>{{cite web|title=200 metres final |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=11 August 2005 |url=http://www.iaaf.net/history/WCH/season=2005/eventCode=3365/results/bydiscipline/disctype=4/sex=M/discCode=200/combCode=hash/roundCode=f/results.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203054703/http://www.iaaf.net/history/WCH/season%3D2005/eventCode%3D3365/results/bydiscipline/disctype%3D4/sex%3DM/discCode%3D200/combCode%3Dhash/roundCode%3Df/results.html |url-status=dead |archive-date= 3 December 2013 |access-date=17 August 2008}}</ref> Injuries were preventing him from completing a full professional athletics season, and the eighteen-year-old Bolt still had not proven his mettle in the major world-athletics competitions.<ref name=FullSeason>{{cite web|last=Smith |first=Gary |title=Bolt preparing to complete a full season, says manager |publisher=Caribbean Net News |date=18 May 2006 |url=http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/cgi-script/csArticles/articles/000016/001647.htm |access-date=28 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080525223450/http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/cgi-script/csArticles/articles/000016/001647.htm |archive-date=25 May 2008 }}</ref> However, his appearance made him the youngest ever person to appear in a 200 m world final.<ref>Butler, Mark et al. (2013). [http://iaaf-ebooks.s3.amazonaws.com/Moscow-2013-Statistics/sources/projet/IAAF-Moscow.pdf IAAF Statistics Book Moscow 2013] ([https://web.archive.org/web/20141012091910/http://iaaf-ebooks.s3.amazonaws.com/Moscow-2013-Statistics/sources/projet/IAAF-Moscow.pdf archived]), pp. 35–7. IAAF. Retrieved 6 July 2015.</ref> Bolt was involved in a car accident in November, and although he suffered only minor facial lacerations, his training schedule was further upset.<ref name=Cautious>{{cite web|last=Smith |first=Gary |title=A cautious Bolt back on the track |publisher=Caribbean Net News |date=24 November 2005 |url=http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2005/11/24/back.shtml |access-date=26 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090822072909/http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2005/11/24/back.shtml |archive-date=22 August 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Smith |first=Gary |title=Jamaica's Bolt recovers from motor vehicle accident |publisher=Caribbean Net News |date=21 November 2005 |url=http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2005/11/21/recovers.shtml |access-date=26 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090822060405/http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2005/11/21/recovers.shtml |archive-date=22 August 2009 }}</ref> His manager at the time, Norman Peart, made Bolt's training less intensive, and he had fully recuperated the following week.<ref name=Cautious/> Bolt had continued to improve his performances, and he reached the world top-5 rankings in 2005 and 2006.<ref name=Focus/> Peart and Mills stated their intentions to push Bolt to do longer sprinting distances with the aim of making the 400 m event his primary event by 2007 or 2008. Bolt was less enthusiastic, and demanded that he feel comfortable in his sprinting.<ref name=Cautious/><ref>{{cite web|last=Cherry |first=Gene |title=Even Bolt's coach convinced of 100m pedigree |publisher=Caribbean News Net |date=23 July 2008 |url=http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/news-9316--8-8--.html |access-date=26 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090822045532/http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/news-9316--8-8--.html |archive-date=22 August 2009 }}</ref> He suffered another hamstring injury in March 2006, forcing him to withdraw from the [[2006 Commonwealth Games]] in [[Melbourne]], and he did not return to track events until May.<ref>{{cite web|last=Smith |first=Gary |title=Bolt runs world leading 200m at Martinique Permit Meet |publisher=Caribbean Net News |date=3 May 2006 |url=http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/cgi-script/csArticles/articles/000014/001462.htm |access-date=26 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080526015824/http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/cgi-script/csArticles/articles/000014/001462.htm |archive-date=26 May 2008 }}</ref> After his recovery, Bolt was given new training exercises to improve flexibility, and the plans to move him up to the 400 m event were put on hold.<ref name=FullSeason/>

The 200 m remained Bolt's primary event when he returned to competition; he bested [[Justin Gatlin]]'s meet record in [[Ostrava]], Czech Republic. Bolt had aspired to run under twenty seconds to claim a season's best but, despite the fact that bad weather had impaired his run, he was happy to end the meeting with just the victory.<ref name=NoSub/> However, a sub-20-second finish was soon his, as he set a new personal best of 19.88 s at the 2006 [[Athletissima]] Grand Prix in [[Lausanne]], Switzerland, finishing behind [[Xavier Carter]] and [[Tyson Gay]] to earn a bronze medal.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Liu eclipses Jackson with 110m hurdles record |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date=12 June 2006 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2006/jul/12/athletics |access-date=17 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130830065833/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2006/jul/12/athletics |archive-date=30 August 2013  }}</ref> Bolt had focused his athletics aims, stating that 2006 was a year to gain experience. Also, he was more keen on competing over longer distances, setting his sights on running regularly in both 200 m and 400 m events within the next two years.<ref name=NoSub>{{cite web|last=Smith |first=Gary |title=No sub-20, but Bolt optimistic about clash with Spearmon at Reebok Grand Prix |publisher=Caribbean Net News |date=2 June 2006 |url=http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/cgi-script/csArticles/articles/000018/001824.htm |access-date=26 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080526103222/http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/cgi-script/csArticles/articles/000018/001824.htm |archive-date=26 May 2008 }}</ref>
[[File:Osaka07 D7A M200M VC.jpg|thumb|right|Bolt (left) on the podium with his silver medal from the 200 m race in [[2007 Osaka World Championships|Osaka (2007)]]. Winner: [[Tyson Gay]] in the center.]]
Bolt claimed his first major world medal two months later at the [[IAAF World Athletics Final]] in [[Stuttgart]], Germany. He passed the finishing post with a time of 20.10 s, gaining a bronze medal in the process.<ref name=IAAFProfile/> The [[IAAF World Cup]] in Athens, Greece, yielded Bolt's first senior international silver medal.<ref name=IAAFProfile/> [[Wallace Spearmon]] from the United States won gold with a championship record time of 19.87 s, beating Bolt's respectable time of 19.96 s.<ref>{{cite web |title=World Cup in Athletics 2006 – Results 200 Metres Mens Final |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=17 September 2006 |url=http://www.iaaf.net/history/WCP/season=2006/eventCode=3490/results/bydiscipline/disctype=4/sex=M/discCode=200/combCode=hash/roundCode=f/results.html |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203052922/http://www.iaaf.net/history/WCP/season%3D2006/eventCode%3D3490/results/bydiscipline/disctype%3D4/sex%3DM/discCode%3D200/combCode%3Dhash/roundCode%3Df/results.html |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref> Further 200 m honours on both the regional and international stages awaited Bolt in 2007. He yearned to run in the [[100 m]]etres but Mills was skeptical, believing that Bolt was better suited for middle distances. The coach cited the runner's difficulty in smoothly starting out of the blocks and poor habits such as looking back at opponents in sprints. Mills told Bolt that he could run the shorter distance if he broke the 200 m national record.<ref name=bftb>{{Cite news |last=Rowbottom |first=Mike |title=Bolt from the blue |work=The Independent |location=UK |date=4 August 2008 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics/lightning-bolt-storms-to-record-in-100-metres-838174.html |access-date=12 August 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023210142/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics/lightning-bolt-storms-to-record-in-100-metres-838174.html |archive-date=23 October 2012  }}</ref> In the Jamaican Championships, he ran 19.75 s in the 200 m, breaking the 36-year-old Jamaican record held by [[Don Quarrie]] by 0.11 s.<ref name=Focus/><ref name=si/>

Mills complied with Bolt's demand to run in the 100 m, and he was entered to run the event at the 23rd Vardinoyiannia meeting in [[Rethymno]], [[Crete]]. In his debut tournament, he won the gold medal in a time of 10.03 s, feeding his enthusiasm for the event.<ref name=si/><ref>{{cite web |title=23rd Vardinoyiannia 2007 – 100Metres Mens Results |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=18 July 2007 |url=http://www.iaaf.net/history/GP/season=2007/results/eventCode=3821/sex=M/discCode=100/result.html |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203055550/http://www.iaaf.net/history/GP/season%3D2007/results/eventCode%3D3821/sex%3DM/discCode%3D100/result.html |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref>

He built on this achievement at the [[2007 World Championships in Athletics|2007 World Championships]] in [[Osaka]], Japan, winning a silver medal.<ref name=IAAFProfile/> Bolt recorded 19.91 s with a [[100 m#Climatic conditions|headwind]] of 0.8 [[Metre per second|m/s]]. The race was won by [[Tyson Gay]] in 19.76 s, a new championship record.<ref>{{cite web |title=Osaka 2007 – 200 metres mens final |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=30 August 2007 |url=http://osaka2007.iaaf.org/results/gender=M/discipline=200/combCode=hash/roundCode=f/result.html |access-date=18 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080916185244/http://osaka2007.iaaf.org/results/gender%3DM/discipline%3D200/combCode%3Dhash/roundCode%3Df/result.html |archive-date=16 September 2008  }}</ref>

Bolt was a member of the silver medal relay team with [[Asafa Powell]], [[Marvin Anderson]], and [[Nesta Carter]] in the 4×100 metres relay. Jamaica set a national record of 37.89 s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Osaka 2007 – 4 × 100 Metres Relay – Mens Final |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=1 September 2007 |url=http://osaka2007.iaaf.org/results/gender=M/discipline=4X1/combCode=hash/roundCode=f/result.html |access-date=18 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915075959/http://osaka2007.iaaf.org/results/gender%3DM/discipline%3D4X1/combCode%3Dhash/roundCode%3Df/result.html |archive-date=15 September 2008}}</ref> Bolt did not win any gold medals at the major tournaments in 2007, but Mills felt that Bolt's technique was much improved, pinpointing improvements in Bolt's balance at the turns over 200 m and an increase in his stride frequency, giving him more driving power on the track.<ref name=bftb/>

===World-record breaker===
The silver medals from the 2007 Osaka World Championships boosted Bolt's desire to sprint, and he took a more serious, more mature stance towards his career.<ref name=BBC10/> Bolt continued to develop in the 100 m, and he decided to compete in the event at the Jamaica Invitational in Kingston. On 3 May 2008, Bolt ran a time of 9.76 s, with a 1.8 [[Metre per second|m/s]] [[100 m#Climatic conditions|tail wind]], improving his personal best from 10.03 s.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tucker |first=Elton |title='I didn't know I was going that fast' – Admits Bolt after rocketing to No. 2 on all-time 100m list with 9.76 |work=Jamaica Gleaner |date=5 May 2008 |url=http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20080505/sports/sports1.html |access-date=6 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080928070331/http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20080505/sports/sports1.html |archive-date=28 September 2008  }}</ref> This was the second-fastest legal performance in the history of the event, second only to compatriot [[Asafa Powell]]'s 9.74 s record set the previous year in [[Rieti]], Italy.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Aikman |first=Richard |title=Lightning Bolt clocks second fastest ever 100m |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date=4 May 2008 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/may/04/usainbolt |access-date=18 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930133410/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/may/04/usainbolt |archive-date=30 September 2013  }}</ref> Rival Tyson Gay lauded the performance, especially praising Bolt's form and technique.<ref name=Kingstun/> Michael Johnson observed the race and said that he was shocked at how quickly Bolt had improved over the 100 m distance.<ref>{{cite web|last=Smith |first=Gary |title=American legend Johnson admits to being 'shocked' by Bolt run |publisher=Caribbean Net News |date=7 May 2008 |url=http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/article.php?news_id=7643 |access-date=26 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090825205533/http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/article.php?news_id=7643 |archive-date=25 August 2009 }}</ref> The Jamaican surprised even himself with the time, but coach Glen Mills remained confident that there was more to come.<ref name=Kingstun>{{cite web |last=Foster |first=Anthony |title=Bolt stuns with 9.76 dash in Kingston – Jamaica International report |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=4 May 2008 |url=http://www.iaaf.net/WAF08/news/kind=100/newsid=44672.html |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203054833/http://www.iaaf.net/WAF08/news/kind%3D100/newsid%3D44672.html |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref>

On 31 May 2008, Bolt set a new 100&nbsp;m world record at the [[Reebok Grand Prix]] in the [[Icahn Stadium]] in New York City. He ran 9.72s with a tail wind of 1.7&nbsp;m/s.<ref>{{cite web |last=Morse |first=Parker |title=Bolt 9.72 in New York! – World 100 metres record – IAAF World Athletics Tour |url=http://www.iaaf.net/GP08/news/kind=100/newsid=45117.html |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=1 June 2008 |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203055345/http://www.iaaf.net/GP08/news/kind%3D100/newsid%3D45117.html |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref> This race was Bolt's fifth senior 100 m.<ref name="CastCloud">{{cite web |url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/other-sports/athletics-cheats-and-liars-cast-cloud-over-bolts-new-100m-record-26450983.html |title=Athletics: Cheats and liars cast cloud over Bolt's new 100m record |last1=Broadbent|first1=Rick|website=[[Irish Independent]] |date=2 June 2008 |access-date=28 November 2013 }}</ref> Gay again finished second and said of Bolt: "It looked like his knees were going past my face."<ref name=si/> Commentators noted that Bolt appeared to have gained a psychological advantage over fellow Olympic contender Gay.<ref name=bftb/>

In June 2008, Bolt responded to claims that he was a lazy athlete, saying that the comments were unjustified, and he trained hard to achieve his potential. However, he surmised that such comments stemmed from his lack of enthusiasm for the [[400 metres]] event; he chose not to make an effort to train for that particular distance.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gn4FpAtTLEtndxAHYe8QfewRPtaA?hl=en |title=Lightning Bolt to run first 200m of season |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |date=11 June 2008 |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226121818/http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gn4FpAtTLEtndxAHYe8QfewRPtaA?hl=en |archive-date=26 February 2014  }}</ref> Turning his efforts to the 200 m, Bolt proved that he could excel in two events—first setting the world-leading time in [[Ostrava]], then breaking the national record for the second time with a 19.67 s finish in [[Athens, Greece]].<ref name=Athens>{{cite web |last=Nikitaridis |first=Michalis |title=Bolt runs 200m in 19.67sec in Athens – IAAF World Athletics Tour |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=14 July 2008 |url=http://www.iaaf.net/GP08/news/kind=100/newsid=46129.html |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203051807/http://www.iaaf.net/GP08/news/kind%3D100/newsid%3D46129.html |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ramsak |first=Bob |title=Robles 12.87 World Record in Ostrava! – IAAF World Athletics Tour |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=12 June 2008 |url=http://www.iaaf.net/GP08/news/kind=100/newsid=45290.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203053245/http://www.iaaf.net/GP08/news/kind%3D100/newsid%3D45290.html |url-status=dead |archive-date= 3 December 2013 |access-date=28 November 2013}}</ref> Although Mills still preferred that Bolt focus on the longer distances, the acceptance of Bolt's demand to run in the 100 m worked for both sprinter and trainer. Bolt was more focused in practice, and a training schedule to boost his top speed and his stamina, in preparation for the Olympics, had improved both his 100 m and 200 m times.<ref name=si/><ref name=JSport>{{cite web |last=Flynn |first=LeVaughan |title=Usain Bolt and Glen Mills: Long, winding journey to a world record |publisher=Sports Jamaica |date=3 June 2008 |url=http://www.sportsjamaica.com/read_article.php?id=12721 |access-date=25 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205123518/http://www.sportsjamaica.com/read_article.php?id=12721 |archive-date=5 December 2008  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Turnbull |first=Simon |title=No Bolt from blue but he can be star of fast show |work=[[The Independent on Sunday]] |date=20 July 2008 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics/100m-showdown-no-bolt-from-blue-but-he-can-be-star-of-fast-show-872321.html |access-date=25 August 2008 |location=London |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108110212/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics/100m-showdown-no-bolt-from-blue-but-he-can-be-star-of-fast-show-872321.html |archive-date=8 November 2012  }}</ref>

===2008 Summer Olympics===
Bolt doubled-up with the [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Olympics – Men's 100 metres|100 metres]] and [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Olympics – Men's 200 metres|200 metres]] events at the [[2008 Summer Olympics|Beijing Summer Olympics]]. As the new 100 m world-record holder, he was the favourite to win both races.<ref>{{cite web |last=Cyphers |first=Luke |title=Bolt may be 100 favourite, but Gay in better position to win |publisher=[[ESPN]] |date=11 August 2008 |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/summer08/columns/story?id=3529300 |access-date=18 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080817093126/http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/summer08/columns/story?id=3529300 |archive-date=17 August 2008  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Gallagher |first=Brendan |title=Beijing Olympics: Usain Bolt set to run in both the 100 and 200 metres |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK |date=6 August 2008 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/olympics/2506738/2008-Beijing-Olympics-Usain-Bolt-set-to-run-in-both-the-100-and-200-metres---Olympics.html |access-date=18 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080817225244/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/olympics/2506738/2008-Beijing-Olympics-Usain-Bolt-set-to-run-in-both-the-100-and-200-metres---Olympics.html |archive-date=17 August 2008  }}</ref> [[Michael Johnson (athlete)|Michael Johnson]], the 200 m and 400 m record holder, personally backed the sprinter, saying that he did not believe that a lack of experience would work against him.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Broadbent |first=Rick |title=Michael Johnson backs Usain Bolt to win sprint duel |work=The Times |location=UK |date=14 August 2008 |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/olympics/article4525478.ece |access-date=18 August 2008 }}</ref> Bolt qualified for the 100 m final with times of 9.92 s and 9.85 s in the quarter-finals and semi-finals, respectively.<ref>{{cite web |title=Beijing Olympics 2008 – Results 100 metres men's finals – Heats |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=15 August 2008 |url=http://www.iaaf.net/oly08/results/eventCode=3659/bydiscipline/disctype=4/sex=M/discCode=100/combCode=hash/roundCode=h/results.html |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203052448/http://www.iaaf.net/oly08/results/eventCode%3D3659/bydiscipline/disctype%3D4/sex%3DM/discCode%3D100/combCode%3Dhash/roundCode%3Dh/results.html |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Beijing Olympics 2008 – Results 100 metres men's finals – Quarter finals |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=16 August 2008 |url=http://www.iaaf.net/oly08/results/eventCode=3659/bydiscipline/disctype=4/sex=M/discCode=100/combCode=hash/roundCode=qf/results.html |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20131128221835/http://www.iaaf.net/oly08/results/eventCode=3659/bydiscipline/disctype=4/sex=M/discCode=100/combCode=hash/roundCode=qf/results.html |archive-date=28 November 2013  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Beijing Olympics 2008 – Results 100 metres men's finals – Semi-finals |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=16 August 2008 |url=http://www.iaaf.net/oly08/results/eventCode=3659/bydiscipline/disctype=4/sex=M/discCode=100/combCode=hash/roundCode=sf/results.html |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203054836/http://www.iaaf.net/oly08/results/eventCode%3D3659/bydiscipline/disctype%3D4/sex%3DM/discCode%3D100/combCode%3Dhash/roundCode%3Dsf/results.html |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref>
[[File:Usain Bolt winning-cropped.jpg|thumb|right|Bolt holds a considerable lead over his rivals in the closing stages of the 2008 100 m final in Beijing.]]
{{quote box|quote="And a fair start, Asafa Powell, Usain Bolt is also out well. Here they come down the track. ''USAIN BOLT! SPRINTING AHEAD, WINNING BY DAYLIGHT!''"|source=—''Tom Hammond, NBC Sports, with the call for the [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Olympics – Men's 100 metres|men's 100 metres]] final at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]].''|width=20%|align=left}}
In the Olympic 100 m final (16 August), Bolt broke new ground, winning in 9.69 s (unofficially 9.683 s) with a reaction time of 0.165 s.<ref name=Berlindata/> This was an improvement upon his own world record, and he was well ahead of second-place finisher [[Richard Thompson (athlete)|Richard Thompson]], who finished in 9.89 s.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Bolt surges to gold in new record |publisher=BBC Sport |date=16 August 2008 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympics/athletics/7565203.stm |access-date=18 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828040356/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympics/athletics/7565203.stm |archive-date=28 August 2008  }}</ref> Not only was the record set without a favourable wind (+0.0&nbsp;m/s), but he also visibly slowed down to celebrate before he finished and his shoelace was untied.<ref name=Top100>{{cite web |title=100 Metres All Time |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=9 August 2008 |url=http://www.iaaf.org/statistics/toplists/inout=O/age=N/season=0/sex=M/all=y/legal=A/disc=100/detail.html |access-date=18 June 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609215448/http://www.iaaf.org/statistics/toplists/inout%3Do/age%3Dn/season%3D0/sex%3DM/all%3Dy/legal%3DA/disc%3D100/detail.html |archive-date=9 June 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Zinser |first=Lynn |title=Bolt Is World's Fastest—by a Mile |work=The New York Times |date=16 August 2008 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/17/sports/olympics/17track.html |access-date=19 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120706102926/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/17/sports/olympics/17track.html |archive-date=6 July 2012  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Casert |first=Raf |title=Olympics: Bolt smashes 100m record |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=17 August 2008 |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/event/story.cfm?c_id=502&objectid=10527480 |access-date=18 August 2008}} {{Dead link|date=June 2010| bot=DASHBot}}</ref> Bolt's coach reported that, based upon the speed of Bolt's opening 60 m, he could have finished with a time of 9.52 s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weltklassezuerich.ch/assets/files/press_releases/2008/en/Bolt%20270808.pdf |title=Usain Bolt: 'Mission accomplished' in Beijing, next stop Zürich |publisher=[[Weltklasse Zürich]] |access-date=26 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707005110/http://www.weltklassezuerich.ch/assets/files/press_releases/2008/en/Bolt%20270808.pdf |archive-date=7 July 2011 }}</ref> After scientific analysis of Bolt's run by the Institute of Theoretical Astrophysics at the [[University of Oslo]], Hans Eriksen and his colleagues also predicted a sub 9.60 s time. Considering factors such as Bolt's position, acceleration and velocity in comparison with second-place-finisher Thompson, the team estimated that Bolt could have finished in 9.55±0.04 s had he not slowed to celebrate before the finishing line.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gullan |first=Scott |title=Scientists say Usain Bolt could have gone faster |work=[[Herald Sun]] |date=11 September 2008 |url=http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,24327608-11088,00.html |access-date=10 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080913191954/http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0%2C21985%2C24327608-11088%2C00.html |archive-date=13 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Eriksen |first1=H. K. |last2=Kristiansen |first2=J. R. |last3=Langangen |first3=Ø. |last4=Wehus |first4=I. K. |year=2009 |title=How fast could Usain Bolt have run? A dynamical study |journal=[[American Journal of Physics]] |volume=77 |issue=3 |pages=224–228 |doi=10.1119/1.3033168 |arxiv=0809.0209 |bibcode=2009AmJPh..77..224E }}</ref>

Bolt stated that setting a world record was not a priority for him, and that his goal was just to win the gold medal, Jamaica's first of the 2008 Games.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Simon |first=Simon |title=Bolt of lightning leaves the rest of mankind far behind |work=The Independent |location=UK |date=17 August 2008 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/olympics/athletics/bolt-of-lightning-leaves-the-rest-of-mankind-far-behind-899696.html |access-date=18 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820022226/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/olympics/athletics/bolt-of-lightning-leaves-the-rest-of-mankind-far-behind-899696.html |archive-date=20 August 2008  }}</ref> Olympic medallist [[Kriss Akabusi]] construed Bolt's chest slapping before the finish line as [[showboating]], noting that the actions cost Bolt an even faster record time.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Akabusi |first=Kriss |author-link=Kriss Akabusi |title=Bolt's showboating is a slap for us idealists |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date=19 August 2008 |url=http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/sport/2008/08/19/bolts_showboating_is_a_slap_fo.html |access-date=19 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820122016/http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/sport/2008/08/19/bolts_showboating_is_a_slap_fo.html |archive-date=20 August 2008  }}</ref> [[IOC]] president [[Jacques Rogge]] also condemned the Jamaican's actions as disrespectful.<ref>{{Cite web|title=IOC Rips Bolt for Lack of 'Respect' |url=http://sports.aol.com/olympics/story/_a/bbdp/ioc-rips-bolt-for-lack-of-respect/142750 |agency=Associated Press |date=21 August 2008 |access-date=21 August 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080824005926/http://sports.aol.com/olympics/story/_a/bbdp/ioc-rips-bolt-for-lack-of-respect/142750 |archive-date=24 August 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Broadbent |first=Rick |title=Deluded Jacques Rogge fails to see the champion in Usain Bolt |work=The Times |location=UK |date=21 August 2008 |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/olympics/article4578959.ece |access-date=21 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106182447/http://timesonline.co.uk./tol/sport/olympics/article4578959.ece |archive-date=6 January 2009  }}</ref> Bolt denied that this was the purpose of his celebration by saying, "I wasn't bragging. When I saw I wasn't covered, I was just happy".<ref>{{cite web |last=Landells |first=Steve |title="It was crazy, phenomenal" – Bolt's 9.69 100 metres stuns the Bird's Nest |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=16 August 2008 |url=http://www.iaaf.net/OLY08/news/kind=100/newsid=46772.html |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203053806/http://www.iaaf.net/OLY08/news/kind%3D100/newsid%3D46772.html |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref> [[Lamine Diack]], president of the [[IAAF]], supported Bolt and said that his celebration was appropriate given the circumstances of his victory. Jamaican government minister Edmund Bartlett also defended Bolt's actions, stating, "We have to see it in the glory of their moment and give it to them. We have to allow the personality of youth to express itself".<ref>{{cite news |title=IAAF sides with Bolt on Rogge comments |url=http://stats.washingtonpost.com/olympics/story.asp?i=20080823072826923076508 |agency=Associated Press |work=The Washington Post |date=23 August 2008 |access-date=26 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722072351/http://stats.washingtonpost.com/olympics/story.asp?i=20080823072826923076508&ref=rec&tm=&src=OLYMPICS_DOLY_RUN |archive-date=22 July 2011  }}</ref>
[[File:Usain Bolt before 200 m.jpg|thumb|left|Bolt doing the "Lightning Bolt" just before breaking the 200 m world record in the [[Beijing National Stadium]].]]
Bolt then focused on attaining a gold medal in the 200 m event, aiming to emulate [[Carl Lewis]]' double win in the [[1984 Los Angeles Olympics]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Philips |first=Mitch |title=Bolt's bid for double safely under way |work=Reuters |date=18 August 2008 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-olympics-athletics-bolt-idUSPEK16519320080818 |access-date=23 July 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020043620/http://www.reuters.com/article/2008/08/18/us-olympics-athletics-bolt-idUSPEK16519320080818 |archive-date=20 October 2012  }}</ref> Michael Johnson felt that Bolt would easily win gold but believed that his own world record of 19.32 s set at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]] in [[Atlanta]] would remain intact at the Olympics.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Johnson |first=Michael |title=Michael Johnson: I think my Olympic 200metres world record is safe from Usain Bolt – for now |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK |date=20 August 2008 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/olympics/2586933/2008-Beijing-Olympics-Michael-Johnson-I-think-my-Olympic-200m-world-record-is-safe----for-now---Olympics.html |access-date=20 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820221426/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/olympics/2586933/2008-Beijing-Olympics-Michael-Johnson-I-think-my-Olympic-200m-world-record-is-safe----for-now---Olympics.html |archive-date=20 August 2008  }}</ref> Bolt eased through the first and second rounds of the 200 m, jogging towards the end of his run both times.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Jamaican Bolt second in 200 metres heat |publisher=BBC Sport |date=18 August 2008 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympics/athletics/7567252.stm |access-date=18 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828040412/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympics/athletics/7567252.stm |archive-date=28 August 2008  }}</ref> He won his semi-final and progressed to the final as the favourite to win.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Super Bolt eases into 200 metres final |publisher=BBC Sport |date=19 August 2008 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympics/athletics/7570651.stm |access-date=19 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828072645/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympics/athletics/7570651.stm |archive-date=28 August 2008  }}</ref> Retired Jamaican sprinter [[Don Quarrie]] praised Bolt, saying he was confident that Johnson's record could be beaten.<ref name=Beyond/> The following day, at the final, he won Jamaica's fourth gold of the Games, setting a new world and Olympic record of 19.30 s.<ref name=200wr>{{Cite news |title=Bolt claims 200m gold with record |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 August 2008 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympics/athletics/7572131.stm |access-date=20 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080821044526/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympics/athletics/7572131.stm |archive-date=21 August 2008  }}</ref> Johnson's record fell despite the fact that Bolt was impeded by a 0.9&nbsp;m/s headwind. The feat made him the first sprinter since Quarrie to hold both 100 m and 200 m world records simultaneously and the first to hold both records since the introduction of electronic timing.<ref name=200wr/><ref>{{cite web |title=NEWS FLASH – Bolt does the double with 19.30 seconds WORLD RECORD! |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=20 August 2008 |url=http://www.iaaf.net/OLY08/news/kind=101/newsid=47045.html |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203054706/http://www.iaaf.net/OLY08/news/kind%3D101/newsid%3D47045.html |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref> Furthermore, Bolt became the first sprinter to break both records at the same Olympics.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bolt earns sprint double, breaks world record |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=20 August 2008 |url=http://www.cbc.ca/olympics/athletics/story/2008/08/20/mens-200-final.html |access-date=20 August 2008|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080822195527/http://www.cbc.ca/olympics/athletics/story/2008/08/20/mens-200-final.html |archive-date = 22 August 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> Unlike in the 100 m final, Bolt sprinted hard all the way to the finishing line in the 200 m race, even dipping his chest to improve his time.<ref name=SI200>{{Cite news |title=Bolt cements greatness, sets world record in 200 with 19.30 |work=Sports Illustrated |date=20 August 2008 |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/olympics/2008/writers/tim_layden/08/20/bolt.record/index.html |access-date=21 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080824073514/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/olympics/2008/writers/tim_layden/08/20/bolt.record/index.html |archive-date=24 August 2008  }}</ref> Following the race, "[[Happy Birthday to You|Happy Birthday]]" was played over the stadium's sound system as his 22nd birthday would begin at midnight.<ref name=SI200/>

Two days later, Bolt ran as the [[relay race|third leg]] in the Jamaican [[4 × 100 metres relay]] team, increasing his gold medal total to three.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Bolt grabs third gold and record |publisher=BBC Sport |date=22 August 2008 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympics/athletics/7576737.stm |access-date=22 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828040502/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympics/athletics/7576737.stm |archive-date=28 August 2008  }}</ref> Along with teammates [[Nesta Carter]], [[Michael Frater]], and [[Asafa Powell]], Bolt broke another world and Olympic record, their 37.10 s finish breaking the previous record by three-tenths of a second.<ref>{{cite web|title=NEWS FLASH – World 4x100m record, 37.10s – BOLT and JAMAICA again! |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=22 August 2008 |url=http://www.iaaf.org/OLY08/news/kind=100/newsid=47266.html |access-date=22 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080822215440/http://www.iaaf.org/OLY08/news/kind%3D100/newsid%3D47266.html |archive-date=22 August 2008}}</ref> Powell, who anchored the team to the finishing line, lamented the loss of his 100m record to Bolt but showed no animosity towards his Jamaican rival, stating that he was delighted to help him set his third world record.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jamaica smashes WR in men's relay |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] |date=22 August 2008 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/08/23/2344289.htm?site=local |access-date=22 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915084226/http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/08/23/2344289.htm?site=local |archive-date=15 September 2008  }}</ref> In January 2017 the Jamaican relay teammates were stripped of their gold medals when a blood sample taken from Carter after the race was retested and found positive for a banned substance.<ref>{{cite web |title=Usain Bolt stripped of 2008 Olympic relay gold after Nesta Carter fails drug test |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=25 January 2017 |access-date=25 January 2017 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/jan/25/usain-bolt-jamaica-olympic-relay-gold-nesta-carter-drugs |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125152024/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/jan/25/usain-bolt-jamaica-olympic-relay-gold-nesta-carter-drugs |archive-date=25 January 2017  }}</ref> Following his victories, Bolt donated US$50,000 to the children of [[Sichuan]] province in China to help those harmed by the [[2008 Sichuan earthquake]].<ref>{{cite web |title="Lightning" Bolt donates for children in China's quake zone |work=China Daily |date=23 August 2008 |url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/olympics/2008-08/23/content_6964714.htm |access-date=25 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090929093508/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/olympics/2008-08/23/content_6964714.htm |archive-date=29 September 2009  }}</ref>
[[File:Boltbeijing.jpg|thumb|Bolt poses and celebrates for press photographers after winning the 100 m final at the 2008 Olympics]]

Bolt's record-setting runs caused commentators not only to praise his achievements but to speculate about his potential to become one of the most successful sprinters in history.<ref name="BrillBolt">{{Cite news |last=Longmore |first=Andrew |title=Brilliant Usain Bolt is on fast track to history |work=The Times |location=UK |date=24 August 2008 |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/olympics/article4596711.ece |access-date=27 August 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Steve |first=Nearman |title=Bolt not done yet |work=The Washington Times |date=25 August 2008 |url=http://washingtontimes.com/news/2008/aug/25/bolt-certainly-not-done-making-marks/ |access-date=27 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081230073204/http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2008/aug/25/bolt-certainly-not-done-making-marks/ |archive-date=30 December 2008  }}</ref> Critics hailed his Olympic success as a new beginning for a sport that had long suffered through high-profile drug scandals.<ref name="CastCloud"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-olympics-athletics-review-idUSPEK2157620080825 |title=Bolt's heroics arrive just in time |work=Reuters |date=25 August 2008 |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203035003/http://uk.reuters.com/article/2008/08/25/us-olympics-athletics-review-idUSPEK2157620080825 |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref> The previous six years had seen the [[BALCO]] scandal, [[Tim Montgomery]] and [[Justin Gatlin]] stripped of their 100 m world records, and [[Marion Jones]] returning three Olympic gold medals.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Fordyce |first=Tom |title=The THG scandal explained |publisher=BBC Sport |date=24 February 2004 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/3210876.stm |access-date=27 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060315021043/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/3210876.stm |archive-date=15 March 2006  }}</ref> All three sprinters were disqualified from athletics after drugs tests detected banned substances in their systems.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Johnson dismisses sabotage claims |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 July 2006 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/5230484.stm |access-date=27 August 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Jones returns five medals from 2000 Sydney Olympics |publisher=[[ESPN]] |date=8 October 2007 |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/trackandfield/news/story?id=3054706 |access-date=27 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080926103658/http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/trackandfield/news/story?id=3054706 |archive-date=26 September 2008  }}</ref> Bolt's record-breaking performances caused suspicion among some commentators, including [[Victor Conte]], and the lack of an independent Caribbean anti-doping federation raised more concerns.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Maese |first=Rick |title=A cleaner Olympics? Despite drug test numbers, don't count on it |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=24 August 2008 |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/printedition/la-sp-olymaese24-2008aug24,0,5371815.story |access-date=27 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080827044024/http://www.latimes.com/sports/printedition/la-sp-olymaese24-2008aug24%2C0%2C5371815.story |archive-date=27 August 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Conte |first=Victor |title=Conte: World Anti-Doping Agency needs to beef up offseason steroid testing |work=Daily News |location=New York |date=18 August 2008 |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/2008olympics/2008/08/18/2008-08-18_conte_world_antidoping_agency_needs_to_b.html |access-date=27 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080826161935/http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/2008olympics/2008/08/18/2008-08-18_conte_world_antidoping_agency_needs_to_b.html |archive-date=26 August 2008  }}</ref> The accusations of drug use were vehemently rejected by Glen Mills (Bolt's coach) and [[Herb_Elliott|Herb Elliott]] (the Jamaican athletics team doctor). Elliott, a member of the [[IAAF]] anti-doping commission, urged those concerned about the issue to "come down and see our programme, come down and see our testing, we have nothing to hide".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Broadbent |first=Rick |title=Usain Bolt: a Jamaican miracle |work=The Times |location=UK |date=18 August 2008 |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/olympics/article4551396.ece |access-date=27 August 2008 }}</ref> Mills had been equally ardent that Bolt was a clean athlete, declaring to the ''[[Jamaica Gleaner]]'': "We will test any time, any day, any part of the body...[he] doesn't even like to take vitamins".<ref>{{cite web |last=Flynn |first=LeVaughn |title=Usain Bolt and Glen Mills: Long, winding journey to a world record |work=Jamaica Gleaner |date=3 June 2008 |url=http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20080603/sports/sports9.html |access-date=27 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917084338/http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20080603/sports/sports9.html |archive-date=17 September 2008  }}</ref> Bolt stated that he had been tested four times prior to the Olympics, and all had tested negative for banned substances. He also welcomed anti-doping authorities to test him to prove that he was clean, stating, "We work hard and we perform well and we know we're clean".<ref name=TestsOK>{{cite web|title=Bolt ok with tests|work=Jamaica Gleaner|date=27 August 2008|url=http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20080827/sports/sports1.html|access-date=27 August 2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080829204805/http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20080827/sports/sports1.html|archive-date=29 August 2008}}</ref>

{{quote| text=I was slowing down long before the finish and wasn't tired at all. I could have gone back to the start and done it all over again.| sign=Usain Bolt's thoughts on his 100m sprint at the 2008 Olympics, published in his autobiography ''Usain Bolt 9.58''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bolt|first=Usain|title=Usain Bolt 9.58|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|year=2010|location=London|page=127|isbn=978-0-00-737139-6}}</ref>}}

===After the 2008 Olympics===
At the end of the 2008 athletics season, Bolt competed in the [[ÅF Golden League]], beginning in [[Weltklasse Zürich]]. Despite having the slowest start among his competitors in the 100 m race, he still crossed the finishing line in 9.83 s.<ref name=NoFire>{{Cite news |last=Turnbull |first=Simon |title=No fireworks, or lightning, but Bolt eases to another triumph |work=The Independent |location=UK |date=30 August 2008 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics/no-fireworks-or-lightning-but-bolt-eases-to-another-triumph-913384.html |access-date=31 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006190733/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics/no-fireworks-or-lightning-but-bolt-eases-to-another-triumph-913384.html |archive-date=6 October 2008  }}</ref> Even though the time was slower than both his newly set world record and Asafa Powell's track record, it was still among the top-fifteen 100 m finishes by any sprinter to that date.<ref name=Top100/> Bolt admitted that he was not running at full strength because he was suffering from a cold, but he concentrated on winning the race and finishing the season in good health.<ref name=NoFire/> At the [[Super Grand Prix]] final in [[Lausanne]], Bolt ran his second-fastest 200 m with a time of 19.63 s, equalling [[Xavier Carter]]'s track record.<ref>{{cite web |last=Sampaolo |first=Diego |title=Powell improves to 9.72, Bolt dashes 19.63 in Lausanne – IAAF World Athletics Tour |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=2 September 2008 |url=http://www.iaaf.net/GP08/news/kind=100/newsid=47464.html |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203052138/http://www.iaaf.net/GP08/news/kind%3D100/newsid%3D47464.html |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref> However, it was the 100 m final, featuring Asafa Powell, that drew the most interest. Powell had moved closer to Bolt's world record after setting a new personal best of 9.72 s, reaffirming his status as Bolt's main contender.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Phillips |first=Michael |title=Powell threatens Bolt's 100m record |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date=3 September 2008 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/sep/03/athletics.asafapowell?gusrc=rss&feed=sport |access-date=6 September 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930133228/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/sep/03/athletics.asafapowell?gusrc=rss&feed=sport |archive-date=30 September 2013  }}</ref> Bolt's final event of the season came three days later at the Golden League final in [[Brussels]]. This was the first 100 m race featuring both Bolt and Powell since the final in the Olympics. Both Jamaicans broke the track record, but Bolt came out on top with a time of 9.77 s, beating Powell by 0.06 s. Victory, however, did not come as smoothly as it had in Beijing. Bolt made the slowest start of the nine competitors and had to recover ground in cold conditions and against a 0.9&nbsp;m/s headwind.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Turnbull |first=Simon |title=Bolt win rounds off a golden summer |work=The Independent |location=UK |date=6 September 2008 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics/bolt-win-rounds-off-a-golden-summer-920944.html |access-date=6 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202152445/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics/bolt-win-rounds-off-a-golden-summer-920944.html |archive-date=2 December 2008 }}</ref> Yet the results confirmed Jamaican dominance in the 100 m, with nine of the ten-fastest legal times in history being recorded by either Bolt or Powell.<ref name=Top100/>

On his return to Jamaica, Bolt was honoured in a homecoming celebration and received an [[Order of Distinction]] in recognition of his achievements at the Olympics.<ref>{{cite web |title=Welcoming home our Olympians |work=Jamaica Gleaner |date=5 October 2008 |url=http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20081005/lead/lead2.html |access-date=20 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090507044247/http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20081005/lead/lead2.html |archive-date=7 May 2009  }}</ref> Additionally, Bolt was selected as the IAAF Male Athlete of the year, won a Special Olympic Award for his performances, and was named [[Laureus World Sports Award for Sportsman of the Year|Laureus World Sportsman of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Bolt wins Laureus World Sportsman Award for third time|url=https://www.laureus.com/news/bolt-wins-laureus-world-sportsman-award-third-time|agency=Laureus|date=19 August 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821103632/https://www.laureus.com/news/bolt-wins-laureus-world-sportsman-award-third-time|archive-date=21 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Bolt and Isinbayeva are World Athletes of the Year – 2008 World Athletics Gala |publisher=[[IAAF]] |date=23 November 2008 |url=http://www.iaaf.net/athletes/gala/2008/newsid=48388.html |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203053121/http://www.iaaf.net/athletes/gala/2008/newsid%3D48388.html |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref> Bolt turned his attention to future events, suggesting that he could aim to break the 400 metres world record in 2010 as no major championships were scheduled that year.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Bolt sets sights on 400m record |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=15 December 2008 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/7782760.stm |access-date=16 December 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216015123/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/7782760.stm |archive-date=16 December 2008  }}</ref> <!--In March it was agreed that two-team sprint showdowns between a Bolt-led Jamaica and athletes from the United States will take place from 2010. Two events, one in each country, are planned for May and June.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/7975377.stm|title=US and Jamaica agree sprint clash|publisher=BBC Sport|date=31 March 2009|access-date= 31 March 2009}}</ref>-->

===2009 Berlin World Championships===
[[File:Manchester City Games 2009 - Men's final 2 (crop2).jpg|thumb|right|Bolt (centre) in the starting blocks before breaking the world record for 150 metres (14.35 seconds)]]
Bolt started the season competing in the 400 metres in order to improve his speed, winning two races and registering 45.54 s in Kingston,<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/sportsNews/idUSTRE51L0BB20090222 Bolt maintains improvement over longer sprint] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225062611/https://www.reuters.com/article/sportsNews/idUSTRE51L0BB20090222 |date=25 February 2009 }}. [[Reuters]] (22 February 2009). Retrieved 16 May 2009.</ref> and windy conditions gave him his first sub-10 seconds finish of the season in the 100 m in March.<ref>Clare, Nelson (15 March 2009), [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/4996061/Usain-Bolt-makes-a-winning-start-on-his-return-to-100m-action.html "Usain Bolt makes a winning start on his return to 100m action"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921120833/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/4996061/Usain-Bolt-makes-a-winning-start-on-his-return-to-100m-action.html |date=21 September 2016 }}, ''[[The Independent]]''. Retrieved 16 May 2009.</ref> In late April, Bolt suffered minor leg injuries in a car crash. However, he quickly recovered following minor surgery and (after cancelling a track meet in Jamaica) he stated that he was fit to compete in the [[150 metres]] street race at the [[Manchester City Games|Manchester Great City Games]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iaaf.net/news/kind=100/newsid=50527.html |title=Bolt Manchester date is still on |publisher=[[International Association of Athletics Federations]] |date=12 May 2009 |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203053803/http://www.iaaf.net/news/kind%3D100/newsid%3D50527.html |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref> Bolt won the race in 14.35 s, the fastest time ever recorded for 150 m.<ref name=IAAF>{{cite web |url=http://www.iaaf.net/news/kind=100/newsid=50606.html |title=Bolt runs 14.35 sec for 150m; covers 50m-150m in 8.70 sec! |publisher=[[International Association of Athletics Federations]] |date=17 May 2009 |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20131128221851/http://www.iaaf.net/news/kind=100/newsid=50606.html |archive-date=28 November 2013  }}</ref> Despite not being at full fitness, he took the 100 and 200 m titles at the Jamaican national championships, with runs of 9.86 s and 20.25 s respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/bolt-986-and-fraser-1088-walker-and-phillips |title=Bolt 9.86 and Fraser 10.88; Walker and Phillips excel over hurdles – JAM Champs, Day 2 |publisher=[[International Association of Athletics Federations]] |date=28 June 2009 |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203004828/http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/bolt-986-and-fraser-1088-walker-and-phillips |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/bolt-completes-double-not-100-veronica-campbe |title=Bolt completes double; 'Not 100%' Veronica Campbell-Brown runs 22.40 – JAM Champs, Day 3 |publisher=[[International Association of Athletics Federations]] |date=29 June 2009 |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203004700/http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/bolt-completes-double-not-100-veronica-campbe |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref> This meant he had qualified for both events at the [[2009 World Championships in Athletics|2009 World Championships]]. Rival Tyson Gay suggested that Bolt's 100 m record was within his grasp, but Bolt dismissed the claim and instead noted that he was more interested in Asafa Powell's return from injury.<ref>[https://archive.today/20120629210201/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/8122996.stm Bolt rules out threat to record]. BBC Sport (28 June 2009). Retrieved 29 June 2009.</ref> Bolt defied unfavourable conditions at the [[Athletissima]] meet in July, running 19.59 seconds into a 0.9&nbsp;m/s headwind and rain, to record the fourth fastest time ever over 200 m,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iaaf.net/GP09/news/kind=100/newsid=51614.html |title=Despite the rain, Bolt blasts 19.59sec in Lausanne – IAAF World Athletics Tour |publisher=[[International Association of Athletics Federations]] |date=7 July 2009 |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203053118/http://www.iaaf.net/GP09/news/kind%3D100/newsid%3D51614.html |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref> one hundredth off Gay's best time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/athletics/8139554.stm|title=Bolt storms to stunning victory|date=7 July 2009|publisher=BBC Sport|access-date=7 July 2009|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090708012645/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/athletics/8139554.stm|archive-date=8 July 2009}}</ref>
[[File:100 m final Berlin 2009.JPG|thumb|left|Bolt beating [[Tyson Gay]] and setting a 100 m world record at the [[2009 World Championships in Athletics]] in Berlin.]]
The 2009 World Championships were held during August at the [[Olympiastadion (Berlin)|Olympic Stadium]] in Berlin, which was coincidentally the same month and venue where [[Jesse Owens]] had achieved world-wide fame 73 years earlier. Bolt eased through the 100-m heats, clocking the fastest ever pre-final performance of 9.89 seconds.<ref>Ramsak, Bob (16 August 2009). [http://berlin.iaaf.org/news/kind=108/newsid=52994.html Event Report – Men's 100m – Semi-Final] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090819022536/http://berlin.iaaf.org/news/kind%3D108/newsid%3D52994.html |date=19 August 2009 }}. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved 16 August 2009.</ref> The final was the first time that Bolt and Gay had met during the season, and Bolt set a new world record—which stands to this day—with a time of 9.58s to win his first World Championship gold medal.<ref name="m_100_f_1.jpg"/> Bolt took more than a tenth of a second off his previous best mark, and this was the largest-ever margin of improvement in the 100-m world record since the beginning of electronic timing.<ref name=NY>Clarey, Christopher (16 August 2009). [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/17/sports/global/17track.html Bolt Shatters 100-Meter World Record ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150929084253/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/17/sports/global/17track.html |date=29 September 2015 }}. ''[[The New York Times]]''. Retrieved 16 August 2009.</ref> Gay finished with a time of 9.71 s, 0.02 s off Bolt's 9.69 s world-record run in Beijing.<ref>Ramsak, Bob (16 August 2009). [http://berlin.iaaf.org/news/kind=108/newsid=52999.html Event Report – Men's 100m – Final] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090820042119/http://berlin.iaaf.org/news/kind%3D108/newsid%3D52999.html |date=20 August 2009 }}. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved 16 August 2009.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/08/20/AR2009082004135.html|title=Jamaican Sprinters Such as Usain Bolt Quickly Reshape Nation's Identity|access-date=23 August 2009|date=21 August 2009|work=The Washington Post|first=Paul|last=Farhi|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401025608/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/08/20/AR2009082004135.html|archive-date=1 April 2012}}</ref>

[[File:Usain-bolt-press-conference-berlin-2009.jpg|thumb|Bolt addresses the press in the Mixed Zone at the 2009 IAAF World Championships]]

Although Gay withdrew from the second race of the competition, Bolt once again produced world record-breaking time in the [[2009 World Championships in Athletics – Men's 200 metres|200 metres final]]. He broke his own record by 0.11 seconds, finishing with a time of 19.19 seconds.<ref name="Universal Sports clip">{{Youtube|9EiPCfPROtE|New World Record for Usain Bolt – from Universal Sports}}</ref> He won the 200 m race by the largest margin in [[World Championships in Athletics|World Championships]] history, even though the race had three other athletes running under 19.90 seconds, the greatest number ever in the event.<ref name=TTG>Hart, Simon (20 August 2009). [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/6062060/World-Athletics-Usain-Bolt-breaks-200-metres-world-record-in-19.19-seconds.html World Athletics: Usain Bolt breaks 200 metres world record in 19.19 seconds] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921120841/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/6062060/World-Athletics-Usain-Bolt-breaks-200-metres-world-record-in-19.19-seconds.html |date=21 September 2016 }}. ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''. Retrieved 21 August 2009.</ref><ref name=Final>Mulkeen, Jon (20 August 2009). [http://berlin.iaaf.org/news/kind=108/newsid=53622.html Event Report – Men's 200m – Final] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090822073517/http://berlin.iaaf.org/news/kind%3D108/newsid%3D53622.html |date=22 August 2009 }}. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved 21 August 2009.</ref> Bolt's pace impressed even the more experienced of his competitors; third-placed [[Wallace Spearmon]] complimented his speed,<ref>[http://www.kbtx.com/sports/headlines/53850282.html Wallace Spearmon Earns Bronze In 200 As Three Others Advance To World Champ Finals] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024175954/http://www.kbtx.com/sports/headlines/53850282.html |date=24 October 2013 }}. KBTX (20 August 2009). Retrieved 21 August 2009.</ref> and the Olympic champion in [[Athens 2004]] [[Shawn Crawford]] said "Just coming out there...I felt like I was in a video game, that guy was moving – fast".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/athletics/8213036.stm|title=Awesome Bolt breaks 200m record|date=20 August 2009|publisher=BBC Sport|access-date=20 August 2009|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090821101554/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/athletics/8213036.stm|archive-date=21 August 2009}}</ref> Bolt pointed out that an important factor in his performance at the World Championships was his improved start to the races: his reaction times in the 100 m (0.146)<ref>[http://berlin.iaaf.org/results/bydiscipline/disctype=4/sex=M/discCode=100/combCode=hash/roundCode=f/results.html#detM_100_hash_f 100 Metres – M Final] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130727054341/http://berlin.iaaf.org/results/bydiscipline/disctype%3D4/sex%3DM/discCode%3D100/combCode%3Dhash/roundCode%3Df/results.html |date=27 July 2013 }}. [[IAAF]] (20 August 2009). Retrieved 21 August 2009.</ref> and 200 m (0.133)<ref name=200reaction>Kessel, Anna (20 August 2009). [https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/aug/20/usain-bolt-200m-reaction-world-championships 'I aim to become a legend,' says Usain Bolt as he smashes 200m world record] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927200014/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/aug/20/usain-bolt-200m-reaction-world-championships |date=27 September 2016 }}. ''[[The Guardian]]''. Retrieved 21 August 2009.</ref> were significantly faster than those he had produced in his world record runs at the Beijing Olympics.<ref>[http://www.nbcolympics.com/trackandfield/resultsandschedules/rsc=ATM002100/index.html Men's 200m Final 2008 Olympics] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091103195154/http://www.nbcolympics.com/trackandfield/resultsandschedules/rsc%3DATM002100/index.html |date= 3 November 2009 }}. NBC (20 August 2009). Retrieved 21 August 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.nbcolympics.com/trackandfield/resultsandschedules/rsc=ATM001100/index.html Men's 100m Final 2008 Olympics] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091103200013/http://www.nbcolympics.com/trackandfield/resultsandschedules/rsc%3DATM001100/index.html |date= 3 November 2009 }}. NBC (20 August 2009). Retrieved 21 August 2009.</ref> However, he, together with other members of Jamaican 4×100 m relay team, fell short of their own world record of 37.10 s set at [[2008 Summer Olympics]] by timing 37.31 s, which is, however, a championship record and the second fastest time in history at that date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trackalerts.com/?p=2812|title=Jamaica dominates the 400 meter relays|date=22 August 2009|publisher=trackalerts.com|access-date=14 February 2010|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090829130629/http://www.trackalerts.com/?p=2812|archive-date=29 August 2009}}</ref>
[[File:Frater Bolt Powell Berlin 2009.JPG|thumb|[[Michael Frater]], Bolt, and [[Asafa Powell]] after winning the 4×100 m relay. [[Steve Mullings]] is missing from the picture.]]
On the last day of the Berlin Championships, the [[Governing Mayor of Berlin]], [[Klaus Wowereit]], presented Bolt with a 12-foot high section of the [[Berlin Wall]] in a small ceremony, saying Bolt had shown that "one can tear down walls that had been considered as insurmountable."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/trackandfield/news/story?id=4417296 |publisher=ESPN |title=Grateful Usain Bolt given 3-ton piece of Berlin Wall |date=23 August 2009|url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090827041159/http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/trackandfield/news/story?id=4417296 |archive-date=27 August 2009  }}</ref> The nearly three-ton segment was delivered to the Jamaica Military Museum in [[Kingston, Jamaica|Kingston]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20100211/sports/sports7.html |publisher=The Gleaner |title=Bolt's Berlin Wall unveiled ... two-ton gift at Up Park Camp |date=11 February 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414155029/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20100211/sports/sports7.html |archive-date=14 April 2016  }}</ref>

Several days after Bolt broke the world records in 100 and 200 metres events, [[Mike Powell (athlete)|Mike Powell]], the world record holder in [[long jump]] (8.95 metres set in 1991) argued that Bolt could become the first man to jump over 9 metres, the long jump event being "a perfect fit for his speed and height".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.com/athletics/berlin/2009/powell-bolt-should-jump_sto2037947/story.shtml|agency=Reuters|date=21 August 2009|title=Powell: Bolt could beat long jump WR}}</ref> At the end of the season, he was selected as the IAAF World Athlete of the Year for the second year running.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iaaf.net/athletes/gala/2009/newsid=54949.html |title=Bolt and Richards are World Athletes of the Year – 2009 World Athletics Gala |publisher=[[International Association of Athletics Federations]] |date=22 November 2009 |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203065305/http://www.iaaf.net/athletes/gala/2009/newsid%3D54949.html |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref>

===2010 Diamond League and broken streak===
Early on in the 2010 outdoor season, Bolt ran 19.56 seconds in the 200 m in Kingston, Jamaica for the fourth-fastest run of all-time, although he stated that he had no record breaking ambitions for the forthcoming season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/bolt-sizzles-1956-in-200m-opener-in-kingston |title=Bolt sizzles 19.56 in 200m opener in Kingston |publisher=[[International Association of Athletics Federations]] |date=2 May 2010 |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203024306/http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/bolt-sizzles-1956-in-200m-opener-in-kingston |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref> He took to the international circuit May with wins in East Asia at the [[Colorful Daegu Pre-Championships Meeting]] and then a comfortable win in his [[2010 IAAF Diamond League]] debut at the [[Shanghai Golden Grand Prix]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/8687722.stm |title=Dominant Usain Bolt wins season opener in South Korea |work=BBC News |date=19 May 2010 |access-date=18 May 2014 }}</ref><ref>Broadbent, Rick (24 May 2010). [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/more_sport/athletics/article7134556.ece Usain Bolt cool on records after sparkling Diamond League debut] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601131927/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/more_sport/athletics/article7134556.ece |date=1 June 2010 }}. ''[[The Times]]''. Retrieved 8 August 2010.</ref> Bolt made an attempt to break Michael Johnson's best time over the rarely competed 300 metres event at the [[Golden Spike Ostrava|Golden Spike]] meeting in Ostrava. He failed to match Johnson's ten-year-old record of 30.85 and suffered a setback in that his 30.97-second run in wet weather had left him with an [[Achilles tendon]] problem.<ref>Hart, Simon (8 July 2010). [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/7877772/Usain-Bolt-urged-by-doctors-to-stick-with-100m-until-injury-worries-clear.html Usain Bolt urged by doctors to stick with 100m until injury worries clear] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011001556/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/7877772/Usain-Bolt-urged-by-doctors-to-stick-with-100m-until-injury-worries-clear.html |date=11 October 2016 }}. ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''. Retrieved 8 August 2010.</ref><ref>Hart, Simon (27 May 2010). [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/7773462/Usain-Bolt-falls-just-short-of-300m-world-record-at-Golden-Spike-meeting-in-Ostrava.html Usain Bolt falls just short of 300 m world record at Golden Spike meeting in Ostrava] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011001550/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/7773462/Usain-Bolt-falls-just-short-of-300m-world-record-at-Golden-Spike-meeting-in-Ostrava.html |date=11 October 2016 }}. ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''. Retrieved 8 August 2010.</ref>

After his return from injury a month later, Bolt asserted himself with a 100 m win at the Athletissima meeting in Lausanne (9.82 seconds) and a victory over Asafa Powell at [[Meeting Areva]] in Paris (9.84 seconds).<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/trackandfield/news/story?id=5364649 Bolt beats Blake, Martina] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115140319/http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/trackandfield/news/story?id=5364649 |date=15 January 2016 }}. [[ESPN]] (8 July 2010). Retrieved 8 August 2010.</ref><ref>[https://archive.today/20120629210159/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/8826489.stm Bolt beats rival Powell in Paris Diamond League 100m]. BBC Sport (16 July 2010). Retrieved 8 August 2010.</ref> Despite this run of form, he suffered only the second loss of his career in a 100 m final at the [[DN Galan]]. Tyson Gay soundly defeated him with a run of 9.84 to Bolt's 9.97 seconds, and the Jamaican reflected that he had slacked off in training early in the season while Gay had been better prepared and in a better condition.<ref>[https://archive.today/20120629210203/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/8887522.stm Tyson Gay beats Usain Bolt over 100 m for first time]. BBC Sport (6 August 2010). Retrieved 8 August 2010.</ref> This marked Bolt's first loss to Gay in the 100 m, which coincidentally occurred in the same stadium where Powell had beaten Bolt for the first time two years earlier.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/report/stockholm-packs-in-tight-to-see-gay-finish-we |title=Stockholm packs in tight to see Gay finish well clear of Bolt, 9.84–9.97 – REPORT – Samsung Diamond League |publisher=[[International Association of Athletics Federations]] |date=6 August 2010 |access-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203024254/http://www.iaaf.org/news/report/stockholm-packs-in-tight-to-see-gay-finish-we |archive-date=3 December 2013  }}</ref>

===2011 World Championships===
[[File:Usain Bolt 200 m final Daegu 2011.jpg|thumb|Bolt during the 200 m final at the [[2011 World Championships in Athletics|2011 World Championships]] in [[Daegu]].]]
Bolt went undefeated over 100&nbsp;m and 200&nbsp;m in the [[2011 in athletics (track and field)|2011 season]]. He began with wins in Rome and Ostrava in May.<ref name=2011List100>[https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/100-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2011 senior outdoor 2011 100 Metres men] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161101005632/https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/100-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2011 |date=1 November 2016 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref> He ran his first 200&nbsp;m in over a year in Oslo that June and his time of 19.86 seconds was a world-leading one. Two further 200&nbsp;m wins came in Paris and Stockholm the following month, as did a 100&nbsp;m in Monaco, though he was a tenth of a second slower than compatriot Asafa Powell before the world championships.<ref>Rowbottom, Mike (4 January 2012). [https://www.iaaf.org/news/news/2011-samsung-diamond-league-review-part-1-1 2011 Samsung Diamond League REVIEW – Part 1] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130623100225/http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/2011-samsung-diamond-league-review-part-1-1 |date=23 June 2013 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref>

Considered the favourite to win in the [[2011 World Championships in Athletics – Men's 100 metres|100 metres]] at the [[2011 World Championships in Athletics|2011 World Championships]] in [[Daegu]], Bolt was eliminated from the final, breaking "ridiculously early" according to the starter in an interview for BBC Sport, and receiving a [[false start]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/olympics/trackandfield/story/_/id/6903427/world-championships-usain-bolt-eliminated-100-meter-final-false-start |title=Usain Bolt false starts, eliminated in final |date=28 August 2011 |publisher=ESPN |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303191145/http://espn.go.com/olympics/trackandfield/story/_/id/6903427/world-championships-usain-bolt-eliminated-100-meter-final-false-start |archive-date=3 March 2016  }}</ref> This proved to be the highest profile disqualification for a false start since the IAAF changed the rules that previously allowed one false start per race. The disqualification caused some to question the new rule, with former world champion [[Kim Collins]] saying it was "a sad night for athletics". Usain Bolt's countryman, [[Yohan Blake]], won in a comparatively slow 9.92 seconds.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/14698558 World Athletics 2011: Bolt disqualified as Blake wins gold] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510144555/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/14698558 |date=10 May 2016 }}. BBC Sport. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref>

[[File:Usain Bolt 2011-09-04 001.jpg|thumb|left|Bolt celebrating his relay victory at the 2011 World Championships]]

In the [[2011 World Championships in Athletics – Men's 200 metres|World Championships 200 m]], Bolt cruised through to the final which he won in a time of 19.40.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bolt claims 200 m gold in Daegu with dominant run|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/SPORT/09/03/athletics.bolt.wins.pistorius/|publisher=CNN|access-date=3 September 2011|date=3 September 2011|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402151804/http://edition.cnn.com/2011/SPORT/09/03/athletics.bolt.wins.pistorius/|archive-date=2 April 2012}}</ref> Though this was short of his world record times of the two previous major tournaments, it was the fourth fastest run ever at that point, after his own records and Michael Johnson's former record, and left him three tenths of a second ahead of runner-up [[Walter Dix]]. This achievement made Bolt one of only two men to win consecutive 200&nbsp;m world titles, alongside [[Calvin Smith]].<ref>Johnson, Len (3 September 2011). [https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/mens-200m-final-bolt-blasts-to-1940-victo Men's 200m – Final – Bolt blasts to 19.40 victory] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810084431/https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/mens-200m-final-bolt-blasts-to-1940-victo |date=10 August 2016 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref> Bolt closed the championships with another gold with Jamaica in the 4 × 100 metres relay. Nesta Carter and Michael Frater joined world champions Bolt and Blake to set a world record time of 37.04.<ref>Johnson, Len (4 September 2011). [https://www.iaaf.org/news/news/mens-4x100m-relay-final-3704-world-record Men's 4x100m Relay – Final – 37.04 World record for Jamaica!] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810084434/https://www.iaaf.org/news/news/mens-4x100m-relay-final-3704-world-record |date=10 August 2016 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref>

Following the World Championships, Bolt ran 9.85 seconds for the 100&nbsp;m to win in Zagreb before setting the year's best time of 9.76 seconds at the [[Memorial Van Damme]]. This run was overshadowed by Jamaican rival Blake's unexpected run of 19.26 seconds in the 200&nbsp;m at the same meeting, which brought him within seven hundredths of Bolt's world record.<ref>Rowbottom, Mike (16 September 2011). [https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/blake-upstages-the-world-in-brussels-report Blake upstages the world in Brussels – REPORT – Samsung Diamond League, FINAL] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810085028/https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/blake-upstages-the-world-in-brussels-report |date=10 August 2016 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref> Although Bolt failed to win the Diamond Race in a specific event, he was not beaten on the [[2011 IAAF Diamond League]] circuit, taking three wins in each of his specialities that year.<ref name=2011List100/><ref>[https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/200-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2011 senior outdoor 2011 200 Metres men] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810073956/https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/200-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2011 |date=10 August 2016 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref>

===2012 Summer Olympics===
[[File:London 2012 Olympic 100m final start.jpg|thumb|right|Bolt at the start of his record-breaking win during the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's 100 metres#Final|100 metres final]] at the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Summer Olympics]].]]
Bolt began the [[2012 in athletics (track and field)|2012 season]] with a leading 100&nbsp;m time of 9.82 seconds in May.<ref>[https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/bolts-982-100m-seasons-debut-one-of-four-worl Bolt's 9.82 100m season's debut one of four world leading performances in Kingston – IAAF World Challenge] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810085941/https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/bolts-982-100m-seasons-debut-one-of-four-worl |date=10 August 2016 }}. IAAF (6 May 2012). Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref> He defeated Asafa Powell with runs of 9.76 seconds in Rome and 9.79 in Oslo.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/olympics/18352622| title=Usain Bolt pips Asafa Powell in Diamond League 100m| date=8 June 2012| url-status=live| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608092903/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/olympics/18352622| archive-date=8 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the Jamaican Athletics Championships, he lost to Yohan Blake, first in the 200&nbsp;m and then in the 100&nbsp;m, with his younger rival setting leading times for the year.<ref>[https://www.iaaf.org/news/news/more-upsets-in-kingston-blake-defeats-bolt More upsets in Kingston – Blake defeats Bolt at 200m, Fraser-Pryce a double winner – Jamaican Olympic Trials, Day 4] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810085318/https://www.iaaf.org/news/news/more-upsets-in-kingston-blake-defeats-bolt |date=10 August 2016 }}. IAAF (2 July 2012). Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref><ref>[https://www.iaaf.org/news/news/blake-defeats-bolt-with-sizzling-975-fraser-p Blake defeats Bolt with sizzling 9.75, Fraser-Pryce dazzles with 10.70 national record in Kingston – Jamaican Olympic Trials, Day 2] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810082749/https://www.iaaf.org/news/news/blake-defeats-bolt-with-sizzling-975-fraser-p |date=10 August 2016 }}. IAAF (30 June 2012). Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref>

However, at the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London Olympics]], he won the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's 100 metres|100 metres]] gold medal with a time of 9.63 seconds, improving upon his own Olympic record and duplicating his gold medal from the 2008 Beijing Olympics. Blake was the silver medallist with a time of 9.75 seconds.<ref>Guardian, Sean Ingle [https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/aug/05/olympics-100m-final-usain-bolt-live?newsfeed=true Olympics 100m final] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927195354/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/aug/05/olympics-100m-final-usain-bolt-live?newsfeed=true |date=27 September 2016 }} 5 August 2012</ref><ref>{{YouTube|id=5ap5uPzdEUs|title=Olympics snapshots: Usain Bolt wins gold in men's 100m final – Rough Cuts}}</ref> Following the race, seventh-place finisher [[Richard Thompson (athlete)|Richard Thompson]] of Trinidad and Tobago declared "There's no doubt he's the greatest sprinter of all time", while ''[[USA Today]]'' referred to Bolt as a Jamaican "national hero", noting that his victory came just hours before Jamaica was to celebrate the 50th anniversary of its independence from the United Kingdom.<ref name="USAToday86">Lopresti, Mike (6 August 2012) [https://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/london/track/story/2012-08-05/Usain-Bolt-mens-100-meters-London-Olympics-Mike-Lopresti/56812856/1 Usain Bolt Builds Cult of Personality 9.63 Seconds at a Time] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310191735/http://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/london/track/story/2012-08-05/Usain-Bolt-mens-100-meters-London-Olympics-Mike-Lopresti/56812856/1 |date=10 March 2016 }}.  ''[[USA Today]]''.</ref> With his 2012 win, Bolt became the first man to successfully defend an Olympic sprint title since [[Carl Lewis]] in 1988.<ref>{{cite news |author=Kessel, Anna |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/aug/05/usain-bolt-olympic |title=Usain Bolt takes 100 m Olympic gold – this time even faster &#124; Sport |work=The Guardian |access-date=6 August 2012 |location=London |date=5 August 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107153633/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/aug/05/usain-bolt-olympic |archive-date=7 January 2014  }}</ref>

{{quote| text=I'm now a legend. I'm also the greatest athlete to live.| sign=Usain Bolt, after winning his seventh straight title in the 100 and 200 m, 9 August 2012<ref name="NBClegend">[http://www.nbcolympics.com/news-blogs/track-and-field/bolt-wins-200-declares-hes-a-legend.html Bolt Wins 200, Declares he's a "Legend"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120810070845/http://www.nbcolympics.com/news-blogs/track-and-field/bolt-wins-200-declares-hes-a-legend.html |date=10 August 2012 }} by Alan Abrahamson, ''[[NBC]] Olympics'', 9 August 2012</ref>}}

Bolt followed this up with a successful defence of his [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's 200 metres|Olympic 200 metres]] title with a time of 19.32 seconds, followed by Blake at 19.44 and [[Warren Weir]] at 19.84 to complete a Jamaican podium sweep. With this, Bolt became the first man in history to defend both the 100 m and 200 m Olympic sprint titles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctvolympics.ca/athletics/news/article/bolt-completes-historic-double-with-gold-200m.html |title=Bolt Completes Historic Double with Gold in 200 m |work=[[CTV Olympics]] |date=9 August 2012 |access-date=9 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120809221831/http://www.ctvolympics.ca/athletics/news/article/bolt-completes-historic-double-with-gold-200m.html |archive-date=9 August 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/london-olympics-2012/news/Usain-Bolt-wins-200m-Olympic-gold-to-seal-unique-sprint-double/articleshow/15427038.cms |title=Usain Bolt wins 200m Olympic gold to seal unique sprint double |access-date=10 August 2012 |work=The Times of India |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120809223345/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/london-olympics-2012/news/Usain-Bolt-wins-200m-Olympic-gold-to-seal-unique-sprint-double/articleshow/15427038.cms |archive-date=9 August 2012 }}</ref> He was dramatic in victory: in the final metres of the 200 m race, Bolt placed his fingers on his lips, gesturing to silence his critics, and after crossing the line he completed five push-ups – one for each of his Olympic gold medals.<ref name="NBClegend"/><ref name = "Newsday"/><ref>{{YouTube|id=A2EaBYfrrLU|title= Olympics Snapshots: Bolt is lightning in the 200 meter sprint – Rough Cuts}}</ref>

[[File:Usain Bolt 2012 Olympics 2.jpg|thumb|left|Bolt at the start of the 2012 Olympic 200&nbsp;m]]
On the final day of the 2012 Olympic athletics, Bolt participated in Jamaica's gold medal-winning [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's 4 × 100 metres relay|4×100 metres relay]] team along with [[Nesta Carter]], [[Michael Frater]] and Blake. With a time of 36.84 seconds, they knocked two tenths of a second from their previous world record from 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/Jamaica-shatters-world-record-in-4X100m-relays |title=Jamaica shatters world record in 4X100m relays |work=[[Jamaica Observer]] |date=11 August 2012 |access-date=11 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120813181636/http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/Jamaica-shatters-world-record-in-4X100m-relays |archive-date=13 August 2012  }}</ref> He celebrated by imitating the "[[Mo Farah#"Mobot"|Mobot]]" celebration of [[Mo Farah]], who had claimed a long-distance track double for the host nation.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/aug/12/london-2012-mo-farah-usain-bolt-tribute Mo Farah honoured by Usain Bolt 'Mobot' tribute] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925005346/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/aug/12/london-2012-mo-farah-usain-bolt-tribute |date=25 September 2016 }}. Retrieved 12 August 2012</ref>

[[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC) President [[Jacques Rogge]] initially stated that Bolt was not yet a "legend" and would not deserve such acclaim until the end of his career,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/rogge-usain-bolt-not-legend-005941723--oly.html |title=Rogge: Usain Bolt not a 'legend' yet |agency=Associated Press |publisher=[[Yahoo!]] |last=Wilson |first=Stephen |date=9 August 2012 |access-date=13 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314041001/http://sports.yahoo.com/news/rogge-usain-bolt-not-legend-005941723--oly.html |archive-date=14 March 2013 }}</ref> but later called him the best sprinter of all time.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sports.inquirer.net/57981/ioc-chief-bolt-is-active-performance-legend |title=IOC chief: Bolt is active performance legend |agency=Associated Press |publisher=Sports Inquirer |date=12 August 2012 |access-date=13 August 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120814174453/http://sports.inquirer.net/57981/ioc-chief-bolt-is-active-performance-legend |archive-date=14 August 2012  }}</ref> Following the Olympics he was confirmed as the highest earning track and field athlete in history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kurtbadenhausen/2012/08/04/how-usain-bolt-earns-20-million-a-year/|title=How Usain Bolt Earns $20 Million A Year|access-date=10 August 2012|date=4 August 2012|work=Forbes|first=Kurt|last=Badenhausen|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120808202741/http://www.forbes.com/sites/kurtbadenhausen/2012/08/04/how-usain-bolt-earns-20-million-a-year/|archive-date=8 August 2012}}</ref>

Bolt ended his season with wins on the [[2012 IAAF Diamond League]] circuit; he had 200&nbsp;m wins of 19.58 and 19.66 in Lausanne and Zürich before closing with a 100&nbsp;m of 9.86 in Brussels.<ref>[https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/100-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2012 senior outdoor 2012 100 Metres men ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810092020/https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/100-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2012 |date=10 August 2016 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref><ref>[https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/200-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2012 senior outdoor 2012 200 Metres men] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810093429/https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/200-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2012 |date=10 August 2016 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref> The latter run brought him his first Diamond League title in the 100&nbsp;m.<ref>Julin, A. Lennart (29 December 2012). [https://www.iaaf.org/news/news/2012-end-of-year-reviews-sprints 2012 – End of Year Reviews – Sprints] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810091335/https://www.iaaf.org/news/news/2012-end-of-year-reviews-sprints |date=10 August 2016 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref>

===2013 World Championships===
[[File:Leichtathletik WM 2013 Moskau 100 m Vorlauf.jpg|thumb|100m heat, Moscow, 2013]]
[[File:Usain Bolt, Anniversary Games, London 2013.jpg|thumb|Bolt celebrating at the [[London Grand Prix|2013 London Anniversary Games]].]]
Bolt failed to record below 10 seconds early season and had his first major 100&nbsp;m race of 2013 at the [[Golden Gala]] in June. He was served an unexpected defeat by [[Justin Gatlin]], with the American winning 9.94 to Bolt's 9.95. Bolt denied the loss was due to a hamstring issue he had early that year and Gatlin responded: "I don't know how many people have beaten Bolt but it's an honour".<ref>{{cite web|title=Justin Gatlin edges Usain Bolt in 100|url=http://espn.go.com/olympics/trackandfield/story/_/id/9349933/justin-gatlin-edges-usain-bolt-001-seconds-rome-100|publisher=ESPN|access-date=7 June 2013|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609171218/http://espn.go.com/olympics/trackandfield/story/_/id/9349933/justin-gatlin-edges-usain-bolt-001-seconds-rome-100|archive-date=9 June 2013}}</ref><ref>Minshull, Phil (6 June 2013). [https://web.archive.org/web/20170129022836/https://www.iaaf.org/news/news/gatlin-upsets-bolt-ahoure-surprises-feix-in-r Gatlin upsets Bolt, Ahoure surprises Felix in Rome – IAAF Diamond League]. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref> With Yohan Blake injured, Bolt won the Jamaican 100&nbsp;m title ahead of [[Kemar Bailey-Cole]] and skipped the 200&nbsp;m, which was won by Warren Weir.<ref>[https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/bolt-books-place-on-jamaican-team-with-nation Bolt books place on Jamaican team with national 100m win] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311153645/https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/bolt-books-place-on-jamaican-team-with-nation |date=11 March 2016 }}. IAAF (22 June 2013). Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref><ref>[https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/fraser-pryce-runs-world-leading-2213-weir-197 Fraser-Pryce world-leading 22.13, Weir 19.79 on final day of the Jamaican Champs ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810175940/https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/fraser-pryce-runs-world-leading-2213-weir-197 |date=10 August 2016 }}. IAAF (24 June 2013). Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref> Prior to the [[2013 World Championships in Athletics]], Bolt set world leading times in the sprints, with 9.85 for the 100&nbsp;m at the [[London Anniversary Games]] and 19.73 for the 200&nbsp;m in Paris.<ref>[https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/100-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2013 senior outdoor 2013 100 Metres men] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119034207/http://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/100-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2013 |date=19 January 2013 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref><ref>[https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/200-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2013 senior outdoor 2013 200 Metres men] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810180223/https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/200-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2013 |date=10 August 2016 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref>

Bolt regained the title as world's fastest man by winning the [[2013 World Championships in Athletics – Men's 100 metres|World Championships 100 metres]] in Moscow. In wet conditions, he edged Gatlin by eight hundredths of a second with 9.77, which was the fastest run that year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Usain Bolt regains 100-meter gold at worlds|url=http://m.apnews.com/ap/db_268750/contentdetail.htm?contentguid=wOsVAYl4|work=Associated Press|access-date=12 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iaaf.org/competitions/iaaf-world-championships/14th-iaaf-world-championships-4873/results/men/100-metres/final |title=100 Metres Result – 14th IAAF World Championships |publisher=iaaf.org |access-date=18 May 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827024248/https://www.iaaf.org/competitions/iaaf-world-championships/14th-iaaf-world-championships-4873/results/men/100-metres/final |archive-date=27 August 2017  }}</ref> Gatlin was the sole non-Jamaican in the top five, with Nesta Carter, [[Nickel Ashmeade]] and Bailey-Cole finishing next.<ref>Johnson, Len (11 August 2013). [https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/report-mens-100m-final-moscow-2013 Report: Men's 100m final – Moscow 2013] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151127105154/https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/report-mens-100m-final-moscow-2013 |date=27 November 2015 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref>

[[File:Usain Bolt 100 m heats Moscow 2013.jpg|thumb|left|Bolt running the 2013 World 100&nbsp;m heats]]

Bolt was less challenged in the [[2013 World Championships in Athletics|200&nbsp;m final]]. His closest rival was Jamaican champion Warren Weir but Bolt ran a time of 19.66 to finish over a tenth of a second clear.<ref>{{cite web|title=Usain Bolt Wins Men's 200 Meters at Worlds|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Sports/wireStory/usain-bolt-wins-mens-200-meters-worlds-19990210|work=ABC News|access-date=17 August 2013|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130818182446/https://abcnews.go.com/Sports/wireStory/usain-bolt-wins-mens-200-meters-worlds-19990210|archive-date=18 August 2013}}</ref> This performance made Bolt the first man in the history of the [[200 metres at the World Championships in Athletics]] to win three gold medals over the distance.<ref>[https://www.iaaf.org/news/feature/lightning-bolt-strikes-three-times-in-200m1 Lightning Bolt strikes three times in 200m] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130826052842/http://www.iaaf.org/news/feature/lightning-bolt-strikes-three-times-in-200m1 |date=26 August 2013 }}. IAAF (18 August 2013). Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref>

Bolt won a third consecutive world relay gold medal in the [[2013 World Championships in Athletics – Men's 4 × 100 metres relay|4 × 100 metres relay final]], which made him the most successful athlete in the 30-year history of the world championships.<ref name=Sweep1>{{cite news |title=Jamaica Sweeps 6 Sprint Events With Relay Golds |url=http://www.pressherald.com/2013/08/18/fraser-pryce-gets-triple-gold-in-4x100-relay-at-world-championships/ |agency=Associated Press |access-date=18 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822142937/http://www.pressherald.com/2013/08/18/fraser-pryce-gets-triple-gold-in-4x100-relay-at-world-championships/ |archive-date=22 August 2016  }}</ref> The Jamaican team, featuring four of the top five from the 100&nbsp;m final were comfortable winners with Bolt reaching the finish line on his anchor leg three tenths of a second ahead of the American team anchored by Gatlin.<ref>Jalava, Mirko (18 August 2013). [https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/report-mens-4x100m-relay-final-moscow-2013 Report: Men's 4x100m Relay final – Moscow 2013] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160321225809/https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/report-mens-4x100m-relay-final-moscow-2013 |date=21 March 2016 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref> Bolt's performances were matched on the women's side by [[Shelly-Ann Fraser-Pryce]], meaning Jamaica took a complete sweep of the sprint medals at the 2013 World Championships.<ref name=Sweep1/>

After the championships, Bolt took 100&nbsp;m wins on the [[2013 IAAF Diamond League]] circuit in Zürich and Brussels. He remained unbeaten in the 200&nbsp;m and his only loss that year was to Gatlin over 100&nbsp;m in Rome.<ref>Jalava, Mirko (2 January 2014). [https://www.iaaf.org/news/news/sprints-review-2013-athletics-iaaf 2013 end-of-year reviews – sprints] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160321103811/https://www.iaaf.org/news/news/sprints-review-2013-athletics-iaaf |date=21 March 2016 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref> For the fifth time in six years, Bolt was named IAAF World Male Athlete of the Year.<ref>[https://www.iaaf.org/news/press-release/bolt-fraser-pryce-2013-world-athletes-of-the1 Bolt and Fraser-Pryce are crowned 2013 World Athletes of the Year] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129235232/https://www.iaaf.org/news/press-release/bolt-fraser-pryce-2013-world-athletes-of-the1 |date=29 November 2016 }}. IAAF (16 November 2013). Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref>

===2014: Injury and Commonwealth Games===
An injury to Bolt's hamstring in March 2014 caused him to miss nine weeks of training. Having recovered from surgery, Bolt competed in the [[Athletics at the 2014 Commonwealth Games|4 × 100 metres relay]] of the [[2014 Commonwealth Games]] in Glasgow. Not in peak form Bolt said that he was attending the Games for the fans and to show his progress since the injury.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ralston |first=Gary |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/commonwealth-games/glasgow-2014-usain-bolt-set-3899910 |title=Glasgow 2014: Usain Bolt set for Commonwealth Games debut in Scotland & admits he couldn't disappoint his fans |work=Daily Record |date=23 July 2014 |access-date=23 June 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150602113316/http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/commonwealth-games/glasgow-2014-usain-bolt-set-3899910 |archive-date=2 June 2015  }}</ref> Bolt and his teammates won the 4 × 100 metres relay in 37.58 seconds – a [[List of Commonwealth Games records in athletics#Men's records|Commonwealth Games record]].<ref>Fordyce, Tom (2 August 2014) [https://web.archive.org/web/20171022104618/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/commonwealth-games/28626118 Usain Bolt: Glasgow 2014 gold for Jamaica in 4x100m relay]. BBC Sport. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref> This was the foremost competition of the year for Bolt, given no Olympics or World Championships in 2014.

In August 2014, Bolt set the indoor 100&nbsp;m world record in Warsaw with a time of 9.98 seconds.<ref>{{cite web |author=Smith, R. Cory |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2174090-usain-bolt-sets-world-indoor-100-meter-record-in-warsaw-national-stadium |title=Usain Bolt Sets World Indoor 100-Meter Record in Warsaw National Stadium |publisher=Bleacher Report |access-date=23 June 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626093936/http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2174090-usain-bolt-sets-world-indoor-100-meter-record-in-warsaw-national-stadium |archive-date=26 June 2015  }}</ref> This was his sole individual outing of the 2014 season.<ref name="senior outdoor 2014 100 Metres men">[https://web.archive.org/web/20160826031554/https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/100-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2014 Senior outdoor 2014 100 Metres men]. IAAF.</ref> Soon afterwards he ended his season early in order to be fit for the 2015 season.<ref>{{cite web |agency=Press Association |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/aug/24/usain-bolt-ends-season-withdraws-zurich |title=Usain Bolt ends his season by withdrawing from Zurich competition &#124; Sport |work=The Guardian |access-date=23 June 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816154008/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/aug/24/usain-bolt-ends-season-withdraws-zurich |archive-date=16 August 2015  }}</ref> In Bolt's absence, Justin Gatlin had dominated the sprints, holding the year's fastest times, including seven of the top ten 100&nbsp;m runs that season.<ref name="senior outdoor 2014 100 Metres men"/><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20151107000432/https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/200-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2014 Senior outdoor 2014 200 Metres men]. IAAF.</ref>

===2015 Beijing World Championships===
At the start of 2015, he intended to make the [[2017 World Championships in Athletics]] his last major competition before retirement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/athletics/31468990|title=Usain Bolt to retire after 2017 Worlds Championships in London|publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 February 2015|access-date=14 February 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216201959/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/athletics/31468990|archive-date=16 February 2015}}</ref>
[[File:Usain Bolt after 200 m final Beijing 2015.jpg|thumb|Bolt after winning his fourth 200&nbsp;m world title]]

Upon his return from injury, Bolt appeared a reduced figure at the start of the [[2015 in athletics (track and field)|2015 season]]. He ran only two 100&nbsp;m and three 200&nbsp;m before the major championship. He opened with 10.12 seconds for the 100&nbsp;m and 20.20 for the 200&nbsp;m. He won the 200&nbsp;m in [[Adidas Grand Prix|New York]] and [[Golden Spike Ostrava|Ostrava]], but his season's best time of 20.13 seconds ranked him 20th in the world going into the championships.<ref name=200WL15>[https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/200-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2015 Senior outdoor 2015 200 Metres men] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320202149/https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/200-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2015 |date=20 March 2016 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref> Two 100&nbsp;m runs of 9.87 in July in London showed better form, but in comparison, Justin Gatlin was easily the top ranked sprinter – the American had times of 9.74 and 19.57 seconds, and had already run under 9.8 seconds on four occasions that season.<ref name=200WL15/><ref name=100WL15>[https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/100-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2015 senior outdoor 2015 100 Metres men] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227182724/https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/100-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2015 |date=27 December 2016 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref> Bolt entered the World Championships to defend his sprint titles but was not the comfortable favourite he had been since 2008.<ref>Johnson, Len (20 August 2015). [https://www.iaaf.org/news/preview/beijing-2015-100m-bolt-gatlin-grasse Preview: men's 100m – IAAF World Championships, Beijing 2015] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810184841/https://www.iaaf.org/news/preview/beijing-2015-100m-bolt-gatlin-grasse |date=10 August 2016 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref><ref>Jalava, Mirko (31 December 2015). [https://www.iaaf.org/news/news/sprints-2015-bolt-felix-schippers-van-niekerk 2015 end-of-year reviews – sprints] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810183117/https://www.iaaf.org/news/news/sprints-2015-bolt-felix-schippers-van-niekerk |date=10 August 2016 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref>

In the [[2015 World Championships in Athletics|World Championships 100&nbsp;m]], Bolt won his semi-final in 9.96, which lagged Gatlin's semi-final win in 9.77 seconds.<ref name=100WL15/> However, Gatlin did not match that form in the final while Bolt improved through the rounds. In a narrow victory, Bolt leaned at the line to beat Gatlin 9.79 to 9.80 seconds. Bolt joined Carl Lewis and [[Maurice Greene (athlete)|Maurice Greene]] on a record three 100&nbsp;m world titles.<ref>{{cite web|title=100 Metres men- – 15th IAAF World Championships|url=http://www.iaaf.org/competitions/iaaf-world-championships/15th-iaaf-world-championships-4875/results/men/100-metres/final/result|website=IAAF|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150823140018/http://www.iaaf.org/competitions/iaaf-world-championships/15th-iaaf-world-championships-4875/results/men/100-metres/final/result|archive-date=23 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/11819155/Usain-Bolt-beats-Justin-Gatlin-by-one-hundredth-of-a-second-in-100m-World-Championship-final.html|title=Usain Bolt beats Justin Gatlin by one hundredth of a second in 100m World Championship final|date=23 August 2015|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=24 August 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150823235952/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/11819155/Usain-Bolt-beats-Justin-Gatlin-by-one-hundredth-of-a-second-in-100m-World-Championship-final.html|archive-date=23 August 2015}}</ref><ref>Johnson, Len (23 August 2015). [https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/beijing-2015-100m-bolt-gatlin Report: men's 100m final – IAAF World Championships, Beijing 2015] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227121410/https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/beijing-2015-100m-bolt-gatlin |date=27 December 2016 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref>

[[File:100 m final moment at 2015 World Championships in Athletics Beijing.jpg|thumb|left|Bolt taking a close World 100&nbsp;m win over Justin Gatlin]]

A similar outcome followed in the [[2015 World Championships in Athletics|200&nbsp;m World finals]]. In the semi-final, Gatlin outpaced Bolt – the Jamaican at 19.95 and the American at 19.87. Despite such slow times prior to Beijing, Bolt delivered in the final with his fifth fastest run ever for the 200&nbsp;m at 19.55 seconds. Gatlin failed to reach his early season form and finished almost two-tenths of a second behind Bolt. Bolt's four consecutive wins over 200&nbsp;m at the World Championships was unprecedented and established him clearly as the best ever sprinter at the competition.<ref>Jalava, Mirko (27 August 2015). [https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/beijing-2015-men-200m-final Report: men's 200m final – IAAF World Championships, Beijing 2015] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227163159/https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/beijing-2015-men-200m-final |date=27 December 2016 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref>

There was also a fourth straight win in the [[2015 World Championships in Athletics – Men's 4 × 100 metres relay|4 × 100 metres relay]] with the Jamaica team ([[Nesta Carter]], Asafa Powell, Nickel Ashmeade, Usain Bolt). The Americans initially had a lead, but a poor baton exchange saw them disqualified and Jamaica defend their title in 37.36 seconds – well clear of the Chinese team who took a surprise silver for the host nation.<ref>Landells, Steve (29 August 2015). [https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/beijing-2015-men-4x100m-final1 Report: men's 4x100m final – IAAF World Championships, Beijing 2015] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227163148/https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/beijing-2015-men-4x100m-final1 |date=27 December 2016 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref>

Conscious of his injuries at the start of the season, he did not compete after the World Championships, skipping the [[2015 IAAF Diamond League]] final.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/34178101 Usain Bolt ends season early and will miss Diamond League final] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817025543/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/34178101 |date=17 August 2016 }}. BBC Sport (7 September 2015). Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref>

===2016 Rio Olympics===
[[File:De Grasse and Bolt Rio 100m final 2016.jpg|thumb|[[Andre De Grasse]] and Bolt after running the 100 m final at the 2016 Olympics.]]

Bolt competed sparingly in the 200&nbsp;m before the Olympics, with a run of 19.89 seconds to win at the [[London Grand Prix]] being his sole run of note over that distance. He had four races over 100&nbsp;m, though only one was in Europe, and his best of 9.88 seconds in Kingston placed him fourth on the world seasonal rankings. As in the previous season, Gatlin appeared to be in better form, having seasonal bests of 9.80 and 19.75 seconds to rank first and second in the sprints.<ref>[https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/100-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2016 senior outdoor 2016 100 Metres men] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201215936/https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/100-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2016 |date=1 December 2016 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref><ref>[https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/200-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2016 senior outdoor 2016 200 Metres men] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221084438/https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/sprints/200-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2016 |date=21 December 2016 }}. IAAF. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref> [[Doping in athletics]] was a prime topic before the [[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio Olympics]], given the banning of the Russian track and field team for state doping, and Bolt commented that he had no problem with doping controls: "I have no issue with being drug-tested...I remember in Beijing every other day they were drug-testing us". He also highlighted his dislike of rival [[Tyson Gay]]'s reduced ban for cooperation, given their close rivalry since the start of Bolt's career, saying "it really bothered me – really, really bothered me".<ref>Brown, Mick (15 July 2016). [http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/projects/usain-bolt/ Usain Bolt on doping and marriage: 'Girls are throwing themselves at you... it's hard to say no'] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716124745/http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/projects/usain-bolt/ |date=16 July 2016 }}. ''Daily Telegraph''. Retrieved on 10 August 2016.</ref>

{{quote| text=I want to be among greats [[Muhammad Ali]] and [[Pelé]].| sign=Usain Bolt on his sporting legacy prior to his final Olympics, 9 August 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Roan|first1=Dan|title=Rio Olympics 2016: Usain Bolt wants to be among greats Muhammad Ali & Pele|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/olympics/37027477|agency=BBC|issue=9 August 2016|date=16 August 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812161512/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/olympics/37027477|archive-date=12 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>}}

At the 2016 Rio Olympics, Bolt won the [[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Olympics – Men's 100 metres|100 metres gold medal]] with a time of 9.81 seconds.<ref name="Rio 100 final">{{cite news|title=Rio Olympics 2016: Usain Bolt wins 100m gold, Justin Gatlin second|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/olympics/36689475|agency=BBC|date=16 August 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816221050/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/olympics/36689475|archive-date=16 August 2016}}</ref> With this win, Bolt became the first athlete to win the event three times at the Olympic Games.<ref name="Rio 100 final"/> Bolt followed up his 100 m win with a [[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Olympics – Men's 200 metres|gold medal in the 200 m]], which also makes him the first athlete to win the 200 m three times at the Olympic Games.<ref>{{cite news|title=How Usain Bolt won his third consecutive Olympic gold in the 200m|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/ng-interactive/2016/aug/19/how-usain-bolt-won-his-third-consecutive-olympic-gold-in-the-200m|agency=The Guardian|date=19 August 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161215102250/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/ng-interactive/2016/aug/19/how-usain-bolt-won-his-third-consecutive-olympic-gold-in-the-200m|archive-date=15 December 2016}}</ref> Bolt ran the anchor leg for the finals of the [[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Olympics – Men's 4 × 100 metres relay|4 × 100 m relay]] and secured his third consecutive and last Olympic gold medal in the event.<ref name="triple triple"/> With that win, Bolt obtained the "triple-triple", three sprinting gold medals in three consecutive Olympics, and finished his Olympic career with a 100% win record in finals.<ref name="triple triple">{{cite news|title=Usain Bolt leads Jamaica to 4x100m gold to complete Olympic triple-treble|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/aug/19/usain-bolt-jamaica-4x100m-gold-olympic-triple-treble-rio-2016|agency=The Guardian|date=19 August 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129204658/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/aug/19/usain-bolt-jamaica-4x100m-gold-olympic-triple-treble-rio-2016|archive-date=29 November 2016}}</ref> However, in January 2017, Bolt was stripped of the 4 × 100 relay gold from the Beijing Games in 2008 because his teammate [[Nesta Carter]] was found guilty of a doping violation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/25/sports/olympics/usain-bolt-jamaica-stripped-2008-olympic-relay-gold-medal-nesta-carter.html|title=Usain Bolt and Jamaica Stripped of 2008 Olympic Relay Gold Medal|last=Mather|first=Victor|date=25 January 2017|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=25 January 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125205131/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/25/sports/olympics/usain-bolt-jamaica-stripped-2008-olympic-relay-gold-medal-nesta-carter.html|archive-date=25 January 2017}}</ref>

===2017 season===
[[File:4x100 men final London 2017.jpg|thumb|right|333px|Bolt after injuring his hamstring in the 4x100 m relay final of the [[2017 World Athletics Championships]]]]
Bolt took a financial stake in a new Australia-based track and field meeting series – [[Nitro Athletics]]. He performed at the inaugural meet in February 2017 and led his team (Bolt All-Stars) to victory. The competition featured variations on traditional track and field events. He committed himself to three further editions.<ref>[http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/inquirer/nitro-goes-off-with-a-bang-returning-crowds-to-athletics/news-story/7fc26c3809c14300385e8a0fc14bcbf8 Nitro goes off with a bang, returning crowds to athletics]. ''The Australian'' (13 February 2017). Retrieved on 13 February 2017.</ref><ref>Rolfe, Peter (8 February 2017). [http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/nitro-athletics-stays-in-melbourne-until-at-least-2019/news-story/3cc27c02df319ee9dd65f2bc9ec66c22 Nitro Athletics stays in Melbourne until at least 2019]. ''Herald Sun''. Retrieved on 13 February 2017.</ref>

In 2017, the Jamaican team was stripped of the 2008 Olympics 4×100 metre title due to [[Nesta Carter]]'s disqualification for doping offences. Bolt, who never failed a dope test, was quoted by the BBC saying that the prospect of having to return the gold was "heartbreaking".<ref name=BBCJan17>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/38744846|title=Usain Bolt loses one Olympic gold medal as Nesta Carter tests positive|date=25 January 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=25 January 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125144538/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/38744846|archive-date=25 January 2017}}</ref> The banned substance in Carter's test was identified as [[methylhexanamine]], a nasal decongestant sometimes used in dietary supplements.

At the [[2017 World Athletics Championships]], Bolt won his heat uncomfortably after a slow start in 10.07, in his semi-final he improved to 9.98 but was beaten by [[Christian Coleman]] by 0.01. That race broke Bolt's 4 year winning streak in the 100&nbsp;m. In his final individual race, in the final, Bolt won the Bronze medal in 9.95, 0.01 behind Silver medalist Coleman and 0.03 behind World Champion [[Justin Gatlin]]. It was the first time Bolt had been beaten at a major championship since the 4×100 m relay of the [[2007 World Athletics Championships]]. Also at the 2017 World Athletics Championships, Bolt participated as the anchor runner for Jamaica's 4×100-metre relay team in both the heats and the final. Jamaica won their heat comfortably in 37.95 seconds. In what was intended to be his final race, Bolt pulled up in agony with 50 metres to go and collapsed to the track after what was later confirmed to be another [[hamstring injury]]. He refused a wheelchair and crossed the finish line one last time with the assistance of his teammates [[Omar McLeod]], [[Julian Forte]], and [[Yohan Blake]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/olympics/story/_/id/20324713/usain-bolt-injured-final-race-career-great-britain-wins-4x100-final|title=Bolt finale ends in injury and collapse, no gold|work=ESPN.com|access-date=13 August 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813050749/http://www.espn.com/olympics/story/_/id/20324713/usain-bolt-injured-final-race-career-great-britain-wins-4x100-final|archive-date=13 August 2017}}</ref>

Following his 2017 season, Bolt had a statue of him unveiled in his honour at the [[Independence Park (Jamaica)|National Stadium]] in Kingston on 3 December 2017.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|last=|first=|date=4 December 2017|title=Bolt statue unveiled in Kingston|work=World Athletics|url=https://worldathletics.org/news/news/usain-bolt-statue-kingston|url-status=live|access-date=1 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201025111403/https://worldathletics.org/news/news/usain-bolt-statue-kingston|archive-date=25 October 2020}}</ref> The statue shows him in his signature "lightning bolt" pose.<ref name=":0" />

==Personal life==
[[File:Usain Bolt 2011 World Athletics Gala.jpg|thumb|right|Bolt with the IAAF men's [[IAAF World Athlete of the Year|Athlete of the Year]] award in [[Monaco]]]]
Bolt expresses a love for dancing and his character is frequently described as laid-back and relaxed.<ref name=BBC10/><ref>{{cite web |last=Fletcher |first=Damian |author2=Armstrong, Jeremy |title=Olympic 100m hero Usain Bolt powered by chicken nuggets and yams |work=Daily Mirror |location=UK |date=18 August 2008 |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2008/08/18/olympic-sprint-hero-usain-bolt-s-chicken-nuggets-diet-secret-115875-20702431/ |access-date=18 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121215958/http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2008/08/18/olympic-sprint-hero-usain-bolt-s-chicken-nuggets-diet-secret-115875-20702431/ |archive-date=21 November 2008  }}</ref> His Jamaican track and field idols include [[Herb McKenley]] and former Jamaican 100&nbsp;m and 200&nbsp;m world record holder [[Don Quarrie]]. [[Michael Johnson (sprinter)|Michael Johnson]], the former 200 m world and Olympic record holder, is also held in high esteem by Bolt.<ref name=BBC10/>

Bolt has the nickname "Lightning Bolt" due to his name and speed.<ref name=Focus>{{Cite news |author1=Lawrence, Hubert |author2=Samuels, Garfield |title=Focus on Jamaica – Usain Bolt |url=http://www.iaaf.org/athletes/jamaica/usain-bolt-184599#biography |work=Focus on Athletes |publisher=[[International Association of Athletics Federations]] |date=20 August 2007 |access-date=1 June 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130604202659/http://www.iaaf.org/athletes/jamaica/usain-bolt-184599#biography |archive-date=4 June 2013  }}</ref> He is [[Catholicism|Catholic]] and known for making the [[sign of the cross]] before racing competitively, and he wears a [[Miraculous Medal]] during his races. His middle name is St. Leo.<ref name="catholicnewsagency1">{{cite news |last=Kerr |first=David |title=Vatican invites Usain Bolt to address religious liberty conference |agency=Catholic News Agency |date=31 August 2012 |url=http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/vatican-invites-usain-bolt-to-address-religious-liberty-conference/ |access-date=4 December 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121208094151/http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/vatican-invites-usain-bolt-to-address-religious-liberty-conference/ |archive-date=8 December 2012  }}</ref>

In 2010, Bolt also revealed his fondness of music, when he played a [[reggae]] DJ set to a crowd in Paris.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newsvideo/weirdnewsvideo/7893446/Usain-Bolt-turns-DJ-in-Paris.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Usain Bolt turns DJ in Paris | date=16 July 2010 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100718101314/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newsvideo/weirdnewsvideo/7893446/Usain-Bolt-turns-DJ-in-Paris.html | archive-date=18 July 2010 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> He is also an avid fan of the ''[[Call of Duty]]'' video game series, saying, "I stay up late [playing the game online], I can't help it."<ref>{{cite news|title=Usain Bolt hooked on Call of Duty but remains anonymous to opponents|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/howaboutthat/10445971/Usain-Bolt-hooked-on-Call-of-Duty-but-remains-anonymous-to-opponents.html|agency=Daily Telegraph|date=16 August 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920015544/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/howaboutthat/10445971/Usain-Bolt-hooked-on-Call-of-Duty-but-remains-anonymous-to-opponents.html|archive-date=20 September 2016}}</ref>

In his autobiography, Bolt reveals that he has suffered from [[scoliosis]], a condition that has curved his spine to the right and has made his right leg {{convert|1/2|in}} shorter than his left.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/20/sports/olympics/usain-bolt-stride-speed.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=6 August 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724012514/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/20/sports/olympics/usain-bolt-stride-speed.html |archive-date=24 July 2017 }}</ref> A result of this is that his left leg remains on the ground 14 percent longer than his right leg, with left leg striking the ground with a force of {{cvt|955|lbf}} and right with {{cvt|1080|lbf}}. [[Biomechanics]] researchers have studied, with no firm conclusions, whether this asymmetry has helped or hurt Bolt in his sprinting career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/20/sports/olympics/usain-bolt-stride-speed.html|access-date=2019-11-14|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Something Strange in Usain Bolt's Stride}}</ref>

He popularized the "lightning bolt" pose, also known as "to di world" or "bolting", which he used both before races and in celebration. The pose consists of extending a slightly raised left arm to the side and the right arm folded across the chest, with both hands have the thumb and [[index finger]] outstretched. His performance of the pose during his Olympic and World Championship victories led to widespread copying of the move, from American President [[Barack Obama]] to small children. It has been suggested that the pose comes from Jamaican [[dancehall]] moves of the period,<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/olympics/rio-2016/2016/08/14/origin-usain-bolt-to-the-world-rio-olympics-2016/88728420/ What's the origin of Usain Bolt's signature celebration?]. USA Today (14 August 2016). Retrieved 1 May 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/11355382/Usain-Bolt-reviews-babies-attempts-at-his-trademark-lightning-bolt-pose.html Usain Bolt reviews babies' attempts at his trademark lightning bolt pose]. ''Daily Telegraph'' (19 January 2015). Retrieved 1 May 2018.</ref> though Olympic sprint champion [[Bernard Williams (sprinter)|Bernard Williams]] also had performed similar celebration moves earlier that decade.<ref>[http://olympics.nbcsports.com/2014/04/07/catching-up-with-bernard-hollywood-williams-track-and-field-olympics/ Catching up with Bernard ‘Hollywood’ Williams]. NBC Sports (7 April 2014). Retrieved 1 May 2018.</ref> His habit of [[fist bump]]ing the volunteers for good luck has been noted in the media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/internetting/usain-bolt-s-fist-bump-of-joy|title=Internetting: a user's guide #21 - Usain Bolt's fist bump of joy|date=19 July 2013|website=the Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/usain-bolt-worlds-fastest-man/2016/08/09/i-still-have-the-hat---its-on-my-wall-the-lucky-volunteers-who-m/|title='I still have the hat - it's on my wall': The lucky volunteers who met Usain Bolt|first=Claire|last=Thomas|date=9 August 2016|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/olympics/rio-2016/2016/08/13/rio-olympics-usain-bolt-beloved-by-fans/88688008/|title=Beloved Bolt 'kind-hearted' and 'really cool'|first=Martin|last=Rogers|website=USA TODAY}}</ref>

===Family===

On 17 May 2020, Bolt's longtime girlfriend Kasi Bennett gave birth to their first child, a daughter named Olympia Lightning Bolt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dancehallmag.com/2020/05/18/news/usain-bolt-welcomes-baby-girl-with-partner-kasi-bennett.html|title=Usain Bolt Welcomes Baby Girl With Partner Kasi Bennett|date=2020-05-18|website=DancehallMag|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/news/20200518/usain-bolt-and-kasi-bennett-welcome-baby-girl|title=Usain Bolt And Kasi Bennett Welcome Baby Girl|date=2020-05-18|website=[[Jamaica Gleaner]]|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/CCWNMuxFp6d/ |website=Instagram |title=I want to wish my gf |last=Bolt |first=Usain |access-date=7 July 2020}}</ref> Bolt and Bennett welcomed twin boys named Saint Leo and Thunder in June 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2021-06-21|title=Usain Bolt shows off huge baby news secret|url=https://www.news.com.au/sport/olympics/usain-bolt-shows-off-huge-baby-news-secret/news-story/e9f7f5e871b050b3cceb326188739656|access-date=2021-06-21|website=NewsComAu|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=2021-06-20|title=Usain Bolt welcomes twins, names one Thunder|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2021-06-21/jamaican-sprinter-usain-bolt-names-child-thunder-twins/100230028|access-date=2021-06-21|website=www.abc.net.au|language=en-AU}}</ref>

===Other sports===
[[Cricket]] was the first sport to interest Bolt, and he said if he were not a sprinter, he would be a [[fast bowling|fast bowler]] instead.<ref name=BBC10/> As a child,admired the bowling of [[Waqar Younis]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Mountford|first=Adam|title=Windies triumph delights Bolt|publisher=BBC Sport|date=8 February 2009|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/tms/2009/02/windies_triumph_delights_bolt.shtml|access-date=9 February 2009|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210112137/http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/tms/2009/02/windies_triumph_delights_bolt.shtml|archive-date=10 February 2009}}</ref> He is also a fan of [[India national cricket team|Indian]] batsman [[Sachin Tendulkar]], [[West Indies cricket team|West Indian]] opener [[Chris Gayle]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Usain Bolt likes to watch Sachin, Gayle|publisher=MSN|date=22 August 2008|url=http://sports.in.msn.com/cricket/stories/article.aspx?cp-documentid=1639772|access-date=23 August 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080822212343/http://sports.in.msn.com/cricket/stories/article.aspx?cp-documentid=1639772|archive-date=22 August 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Australia national cricket team|Australian]] opener [[Matthew Hayden]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Usain Bolt gives respect to cricketer Matthew Hayden|work=[[Herald Sun]]|date=22 August 2008|url=http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,24222032-2882,00.html|access-date=25 August 2008|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080824061648/http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0%2C21985%2C24222032-2882%2C00.html|archive-date=24 August 2008}}</ref> During a charity cricket match, Bolt [[Bowled|clean-bowled]] Gayle who was complimentary of Bolt's pace and swing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/other_international/west_indies/8338865.stm|work=BBC News|title=Gayle returns as Windies skipper|date=2 November 2009}}</ref> Bolt also struck a [[Boundary (cricket)|six]] off Gayle's bowling. Another bowler complimentary of Bolt's pace was former West Indies fast-bowling great [[Curtly Ambrose]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/other_international/west_indies/8313778.stm|work=BBC News|title=Lightning Bolt blows over Gayle|date=19 October 2009|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805185156/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/other_international/west_indies/8313778.stm|archive-date=5 August 2017}}</ref>

After talking with Australian cricketer [[Shane Warne]], Bolt suggested that if he were able to get time off he would be interested in playing in the cricket [[Big Bash League]]. [[Melbourne Stars]] chief executive Clint Cooper said there were free spots on his team should be available. Bolt stated that he enjoyed the [[Twenty20]] version of the game, admiring the aggressive and constant nature of the batting. On his own ability, he said "I don't know how good I am. I will probably have to get a lot of practice in."<ref>{{cite web|title=Usain Bolt to play for Melbourne Stars in Big Bash League?|url=http://www.cricketcountry.com/cricket-articles/Usain-Bolt-to-play-for-Melbourne-Stars-in-Big-Bash-League-/16892|publisher=cricketcountry.com|access-date=12 August 2012|date=12 August 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120814231246/http://www.cricketcountry.com/cricket-articles/Usain-Bolt-to-play-for-Melbourne-Stars-in-Big-Bash-League-/16892|archive-date=14 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/9473832/Shane-Warne-leading-campaign-to-bring-Usain-Bolt-to-Melbourne-for-Australias-Twenty20-Big-Bash-League.html |title=Shane Warne leading campaign to bring Usain Bolt to Melbourne for Australia's Twenty20 Big Bash League |work=The Daily Telegraph |access-date=21 August 2012 |location=London |date=13 August 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120821110913/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/9473832/Shane-Warne-leading-campaign-to-bring-Usain-Bolt-to-Melbourne-for-Australias-Twenty20-Big-Bash-League.html |archive-date=21 August 2012  }}</ref>

Bolt is also a fan of [[Premier League]] football team Manchester United.<ref name="english.rfi.fr">{{cite web|url=http://www.english.rfi.fr/sports/20100718-lightning-bolt-strikes-paris|title=Lightning Bolt strikes Paris|publisher=Radio France Internationale|access-date=18 February 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303225101/http://www.english.rfi.fr/sports/20100718-lightning-bolt-strikes-paris|archive-date=3 March 2012}}</ref> He has declared he is a fan of [[Dutch people|Dutch]] striker [[Ruud van Nistelrooy]].<ref>[http://fourfourtwo.com/interviews/celebrityfans/220/article.aspx fourfourtwo interview] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130727083018/http://fourfourtwo.com/interviews/celebrityfans/220/article.aspx |date=27 July 2013 }}. ''[[fourfourtwo]]''</ref> Bolt was a special guest of Manchester United at the [[2011 UEFA Champions League Final]] in London, where he stated that he would like to play for them after his retirement.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/927021/usain-bolt:-i-could-play-for-man-utd-when-i-retire?cc=5901 |title=Usain Bolt: I could play for Man Utd when I retire |publisher=ESPN Soccernet |date=9 June 2011 |access-date=18 February 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612224542/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/927021/usain-bolt%3A-i-could-play-for-man-utd-when-i-retire?cc=5901 |archive-date=12 June 2011  }}</ref>

In 2013, Bolt played basketball in the [[NBA All-Star Weekend Celebrity Game]]. He scored two points from a [[slam dunk]] but acknowledged his other basketball skills were lacking.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/basketball/usain-bolt-hits-the-hardwood-at-nba-all-star-weekend/article8771612/ |title=Usain Bolt hits the hardwood at NBA all-star weekend |first=Kristie |last=Rieken |date=15 February 2013 |work=The Globe and Mail |access-date=18 February 2013 |location=Toronto |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130217120716/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/basketball/usain-bolt-hits-the-hardwood-at-nba-all-star-weekend/article8771612/ |archive-date=17 February 2013 }}</ref>

In an interview with [[Decca Aitkenhead]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' in November 2016, Bolt said he wished to play as a professional footballer after retiring from track and field. He reiterated his desire to play for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] if given a chance and added, "For me, if I could get to play for Manchester United, that would be like a dream come true. Yes, that would be epic."<ref>{{cite web|last=Aitkenhead|first=Decxca|author-link=Decca Aitkenhead|title=Usain Bolt: 'I feel good because I know I've done it clean'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/nov/12/usain-bolt-feel-good-because-know-done-it-clean|work=The Guardian|date=12 November 2016|access-date=15 February 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211121235/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/nov/12/usain-bolt-feel-good-because-know-done-it-clean|archive-date=11 February 2017}}</ref>

In 2018, after training with Norwegian side [[Strømsgodset Toppfotball|Strømsgodset]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44300269|title=Usain Bolt trains with Norwegian top-flight side Stromsgodset|publisher=BBC Sport|date=30 May 2018|access-date=5 June 2018}}</ref> Bolt played for the club as a forward in a friendly match against the [[Norway national under-19 football team|Norway national under-19 team]]. He wore the number "9.58" in allusion to his 100 m world record.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globoesporte.globo.com/futebol/futebol-internacional/noticia/camisa-958-bolt-estreia-no-futebol-noruegues-com-direito-a-gol-perdido.ghtml|title=Camisa "9.58", Bolt estreia no futebol norueguês com direito a gol perdido|publisher=Globo.com|language=pt|date=5 June 2018|access-date=5 June 2018}}</ref> Bolt wore the same number whilst captaining the World XI during [[Soccer Aid#Soccer Aid 2018|Soccer Aid 2018]] at [[Old Trafford]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-43199296|title=Usain Bolt to finally make Old Trafford debut|date=27 February 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=8 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>

On 21 August 2018, on his 32nd birthday, Bolt started training with Australian club [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]] of the [[A-League]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/video_and_audio/must_see/45263871/usain-bolt-trains-to-be-a-footballer|title=Must See|website=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=21 August 2018}}</ref> He made his [[Friendly Match|friendly]] debut for the club as a substitute on 31 August 2018 against a Central Coast Select team, made up of players playing in the local area.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://globoesporte.globo.com/futebol/futebol-internacional/noticia/ainda-sem-contrato-usain-bolt-faz-sua-estreia-como-jogador-de-futebol.ghtml|title=Lá vem o Raio! Usain Bolt faz sua estreia como jogador de futebol na Austrália|work=Globoesporte|access-date=8 September 2018|language=pt-BR}}</ref> On 12 October, he started in a friendly against amateur club Macarthur South West United and scored two goals, both in the second half, with his [[goal celebration]] featuring his signature "To Di World" pose.<ref>{{cite web|title=Usain Bolt scores twice on first start for Australia's Central Coast Mariners |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45834453 |date=12 October 2018 |access-date=13 October 2018 |publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Usain Bolt Strikes His Signature Pose Celebrating First Goals In Pro Soccer |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/usain-bolt-soccer-first-goals_us_5bc109cde4b040bb4e82483d?guccounter=1&guce_referrer_us=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvLnVrLw&guce_referrer_cs=4uD6GzYMNN8HnOTbX__Fsg |access-date=18 October 2018 |agency=Huffington Post}}</ref>

Bolt was offered a two-year contract from Maltese club [[Valletta F.C.|Valletta]], which he turned down on 18 October 2018.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45899234 "Usain Bolt: Eight-time Olympic champion 'turns down' Valletta contract"]. BBC. Retrieved 18 October 2018</ref> On 21 October 2018, Bolt was offered a contract by the Mariners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/soccer/usain-bolt-offered-contract-by-central-coast-mariners-agent-confirms-20181021-p50b2x.html|title=Usain Bolt offered contract by Central Coast Mariners, agent confirms|last=Wenzel|first=Murray|date=2018-10-21|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2018-10-21}}</ref> The Australian FA was helping the Mariners to fund it.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45963598 "Usain Bolt: Australian FA helping Central Coast Mariners fund deal with Olympic champion."] BBC. Retrieved 25 October 2018</ref> Later that month, [[Perth Glory]] forward [[Andy Keogh]] was critical of Bolt's ability, stating his first touch is "like a trampoline." He added Bolt has "shown a bit of potential but it's a little bit of a kick in the teeth to the professionals that are in the league."<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45988823 "Usain Bolt: Olympic champion has 'touch like a trampoline', says Andy Keogh."] BBC. Retrieved 26 October 2018</ref>

Bolt left the Mariners in early November 2018 after 8 weeks with the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-46068150|title=Usain Bolt leaves Australian football club|date=2 November 2018|work=BBC News}}</ref> In January 2019, Bolt decided not to pursue a career in football, saying his "sports life is over."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/11614773/usain-bolt-gives-up-on-his-hopes-as-a-professional-football-player|title=Usain Bolt gives up on his hopes as a professional football player|last=Fiore|first=Tommaso|date=22 January 2019|work=Sky Sports|access-date=23 January 2019}}</ref>

===Documentary film===
A documentary film based on the athletic life of Bolt to win three Olympic gold medals, titled ''[[I Am Bolt]]'', was released on 28 November 2016 in United Kingdom. The film was directed by Benjamin Turner and Gabe Turner.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4647900/ |title=I Am Bolt (2016) |publisher=IMdb |access-date=11 March 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170212202313/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt4647900/ |archive-date=12 February 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/nov/27/i-am-bolt-usain-review |title=I Am Bolt review – life in the fast lane |work=The Guardian |date=27 November 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170310204714/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/nov/27/i-am-bolt-usain-review |archive-date=10 March 2017  }}</ref>

=== Infection with COVID-19 ===
On 24 August 2020, Bolt tested positive for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] and subsequently went into self-isolation in his home.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Kimble|first=Lindsay|date=2020-08-24|title=Usain Bolt Tested for Coronavirus, Is Not Currently Exhibiting Any Symptoms|url=https://people.com/sports/usain-bolt-says-he-has-coronavirus/|access-date=|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]}}</ref> He said that he was asymptomatic.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Brassil|first=Gillian R.|date=2020-08-24|title=Usain Bolt Quarantines as He Awaits Result of Coronavirus Test|language=en-US|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/08/24/sports/olympics/coronavirus-usain-bolt.html|access-date=2021-02-01|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Bolt had himself tested on 22 August, the day after celebrating his 34th birthday with a party where guests did not wear face masks. Coincidentally, the guests at the party danced in an open field to Jamaican reggae singer [[Koffee (singer)|Koffee]]'s song "Lockdown".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-08-25/usain-bolt-coronavirus-covid19-tests-positive-sprinter/12593018|title=Usain Bolt tests positive for coronavirus after birthday party with friends in Jamaica|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|date=25 August 2020|access-date=25 August 2020}}</ref> Among those who attended the party were [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] football player [[Raheem Sterling]], who was also advised to self-isolate after his possible exposure to the virus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/08/coronavirus-catches-usain-bolt-world-fastest-man-200825015114616.html|title=Coronavirus catches up with Usain Bolt, world's fastest man|work=[[Al Jazeera]]|date=25 August 2020|access-date=25 August 2020}}</ref>

==Sponsorships and advertising work==
[[File:Usain Bolt 2012 Olympics 3.jpg|thumb|Bolt wearing [[Puma AG|Puma]] shoes as part of a sponsorship deal.]]

After winning the 200 m title in the [[2002 World Junior Championships in Athletics|2002 World Junior Championships]] in Kingston, Bolt signed a sponsorship deal with [[Puma AG|Puma]].<ref>{{cite web|title=PUMA's Usain Bolt breaks 100m World Record |publisher=[[Puma AG|Puma]] |date=3 June 2008 |url=http://about.puma.com/EN/3/23/23/news_id=125 |access-date=18 August 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080801210821/http://about.puma.com/EN/3/23/23/news_id%3D125 |archive-date= 1 August 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> To promote Bolt's chase for Olympic glory in the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in Beijing, China, Puma released a series of videos including Bolt's then-world-record-setting run in [[Icahn Stadium]] and his Olympic preparations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pumarunning.com/#EN/running/content/main/chasingBOLT|title=Puma running – Chasing Bolt|publisher=[[Puma AG|Puma]]|access-date=18 August 2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100428114815/http://www.pumarunning.com/#EN/running/content/main/chasingBOLT|archive-date=28 April 2010}}</ref> After his record-breaking run in New York City, which was preceded by a [[thunderstorm|lightning storm]],<ref name=Storm>{{Cite news |last=Rowbottom |first=Mike |title='Lightning' Bolt storms to record in 100 metres |work=The Independent |location=UK |date=2 June 2008 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics/lightning-bolt-storms-to-record-in-100-metres-838174.html |access-date=20 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080605024932/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics/lightning-bolt-storms-to-record-in-100-metres-838174.html |archive-date=5 June 2008  }}</ref> the press frequently made puns on the Jamaican's name, nicknaming him "Lightning Bolt" and the "[[Bolt from the blue]]".<ref>{{Cite news |title=Lightning Bolt's Irish connection |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 August 2008 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/7571436.stm |access-date=20 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828054043/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/7571436.stm |archive-date=28 August 2008  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Lightning Bolt makes giant leap |work=[[Evening Herald]] |date=18 August 2008 |url=http://www.herald.ie/sport/other-sports/lightning-bolt-makes-giant-leap-1458032.html |access-date=20 August 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jpost.com/Sports/Allon-Sinais-Olympic-Diary-A-Bolt-from-the-blue-strikes-the-Nest |title=Allon Sinai's Olympic Diary: A Bolt from the blue strikes the Nest |work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |date=17 August 2008 |access-date=28 November 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204000601/http://www.jpost.com/Sports/Allon-Sinais-Olympic-Diary-A-Bolt-from-the-blue-strikes-the-Nest |archive-date=4 December 2013  }}</ref> During the 2008 Beijing 100 m final, Bolt wore golden Puma Complete Theseus spikes that had "Beijing 100 m Gold" emblazoned across them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/yourturn/viewtopic.php?t=446511 |title=Usain Bolt blazes to top of 100-metre lore |last=Weiner |first=Jay |work=[[Sporting News]] |date=16 August 2008 |access-date=18 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080819011746/http://www.sportingnews.com/yourturn/viewtopic.php?t=446511 |archive-date=19 August 2008 }}</ref> Writing of Bolt's performance at the Olympics, ''[[The Associated Press]]'' said:
{{quote|text=Almost single-handedly, Bolt has helped track transform itself from a dying sport to one with a singular, smiling, worldwide star.| sign=''[[The Associated Press]]'', 10 August 2012<ref name="Newsday">[http://www.newsday.com/sports/olympics/usain-bolt-says-he-s-a-legend-but-isn-t-done-at-olympics-1.3895143 Usain Bolt says he's a 'Legend,' but isn't done at Olympics] by [[The Associated Press]], 10 August 2012 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120812234351/http://www.newsday.com/sports/olympics/usain-bolt-says-he-s-a-legend-but-isn-t-done-at-olympics-1.3895143 |date=12 August 2012 }}</ref>}}

In September 2010, Bolt travelled to Australia where his sponsor [[Gatorade]] was holding an event called the "Gatorade Bolt" to find Australia's fastest footballer. The event was held at the [[Sydney International Athletic Centre]] and featured football players from [[rugby league]], [[rugby union]], [[Australian rules football]], and [[association football]]. Prior to the race Bolt gave the runners some private coaching and also participated in the 10th anniversary celebrations for the [[2000 Summer Olympic Games]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Wallaby winger Lachie Turner named footy's fastest man after 100m race|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/wallaby-winger-lachie-turner-named-footys-fastest-man-after-100m-race/story-e6frexni-1225924289700|agency=Daily Telegraph|date=16 August 2016}}</ref>

In January 2012, Bolt impersonated [[Richard Branson]] in an advertising campaign for [[Virgin Media]].<ref name="Usain Bolt mimics Richard Branson in Virgin Media superfast broadband ad">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/jan/13/usain-bolt-richard-branson-virgin-media|title=Usain Bolt mimics Richard Branson in Virgin Media superfast broadband ad|work=The Guardian|access-date=16 February 2012|location=London|first=Mark|last=Sweney|date=13 January 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131205021248/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/jan/13/usain-bolt-richard-branson-virgin-media|archive-date=5 December 2013}}</ref> The campaign was directed by [[Seth Gordon]] and features the [[Virgin Group|Virgin]] founder Branson to promote its broadband service. In March 2012, Bolt starred in an advert for Visa and the 2012 Summer Olympics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20120320/sports/sports2.html|title=Bolt Stars in Visa Ad|author=Levy, Leighton|date=20 March 2012|work=The Gleaner|access-date=1 April 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322193313/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20120320/sports/sports2.html|archive-date=22 March 2012}}</ref> In July 2012, Bolt and [[RockLive]] launched ''Bolt!'', an [[iOS (Apple)|Apple iOS]] game based on his exploits. ''Bolt!'' quickly became the No. 1 app in Jamaica and climbed the UK [[iTunes]] charts to reach No. 2 on the list of Top Free Apps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mashable.com/2012/07/18/usain-bolt|title=Can Usain Bolt Create an Olympic-Sized Brand?|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723093014/http://mashable.com/2012/07/18/usain-bolt/|archive-date=23 July 2012}}</ref>

In 2012, Bolt collaborated with headphone maker [[Soul Electronics]] to design his own line of headphones. Bolt designed both an in-ear bud and over-ear model with the Jamaican color scheme and his signature "To Di World" pose. Usain Bolt<ref>{{cite web |last1=Manahan |first1=Theresa |title=Usain Bolt designs own line of headphones
 |url=https://www.espn.com/blog/music/post/_/id/1666/usain-bolt-designs-own-line-of-headphones |website=ESPN |publisher=ESPN }}</ref>

Bolt's autobiography, ''My Story: 9.58: Being the World's Fastest Man'', was released in 2010. Bolt had previously said that the book "...should be exciting, it's my life, and I'm a cool and exciting guy."<ref name="english.rfi.fr"/> His athletics agent is [[PACE Sports Management]].<ref>[http://www.pacesportsmanagement.com/athlete_profile.asp?id=158 Athlete Profile Usain Bolt] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203011128/http://www.pacesportsmanagement.com/athlete_profile.asp?id=158 |date=3 December 2013 }}. PACE Sports Management. Retrieved 12 May 2009.</ref>

As part of his sponsorship deal with Puma, the manufacturer sends sporting equipment to his alma mater, William Knibb Memorial High School, every year. At Bolt's insistence, advertisements featuring him are filmed in Jamaica, by a Jamaican production crew, in an attempt to boost local enterprise and gain exposure for the country.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Thomas|first1=Claire|title=10 facts you didn't know about Usain Bolt, the world's fastest man|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/athletics/2017/08/03/10-facts-didnt-know-usain-bolt-worlds-fastest-man/|publisher=The Telegraph|access-date=27 August 2017}}</ref> In 2017, Bolt had the third highest earning social media income for sponsors among sportspeople (behind [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] and [[Neymar]]), and he was the only non-footballer in the top seven.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kurtbadenhausen/2017/06/15/cristiano-ronaldo-produces-nearly-1-billion-in-value-for-sponsors-on-social-media-this-year/ |first=Kurt |last=Badenhausen |date=15 June 2017 |title=Cristiano Ronaldo Produced Nearly $1 Billion In Value For Sponsors On Social Media |work=Forbes |access-date=30 August 2017 }}</ref>

Bolt is the highest paid athlete in the history of the sport.<ref name="paid">{{cite web|title=How Usain Bolt Earns $33 Million A Year--A Whopping 10 Times More Than Any Other Track Star|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kurtbadenhausen/2016/08/12/how-usain-bolt-earns-33-million-a-year-a-whopping-10-times-more-than-any-other-track-star/|website=Forbes|date=12 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Usain Bolt|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/usain-bolt/?sh=4acfac22c805|website=Forbes|date=6 April 2018}}</ref> In 2016, Bolt earned about $33 million in one year putting him at No. 32 on [[Forbes]] list of ''The World's Highest-paid Athletes'' making him the only track and field athlete on the list.<ref name="paid" />

==Entrepreneurship==
Usain Bolt co-founded electric scooter company [[Bolt Mobility]] in 2018, created in his namesake.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/05/16/sport/usain-bolt-electric-scooter-bolt-spt-intl/index.html|title=Usain Bolt: From Olympic sprinter to business co-founder|website=CNN}}</ref> Bolt founded the micromobility company, which provides electric scooters and other yet-to-be released mobility devices, such as the company's upcoming ''Bolt Nano''. Bolt appeared in Bolt Mobility's debut commercial, released through YouTube and his official Facebook account.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/usainbolt/videos/313633599344031/|title=BOLT Mobility Electric Scooters|via=www.facebook.com}}</ref> Bolt appeared in a number of interviews for the company, alongside CEO Sarah Pishevar Haynes. Bolt made his first public appearance for the company in March 2019, during the company's New York City launch and in CNBC interviews on the [[NYSE]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/video/2019/03/14/usain-bolt-and-sarah-haynes-on-e-scooter-company-bolt.html|title=Usain Bolt and Sarah Haynes on E-Scooter company, Bolt|website=www.cnbc.com}}</ref> 
In May 2019, the company expanded its services to Europe, introducing the product first in [[Paris]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://olympics.nbcsports.com/2019/02/02/usain-bolt-having-fun-at-super-bowl-ties-nfl-combine-40-yard-dash-record/|title=Usain Bolt having fun at Super Bowl, 'ties' NFL Combine 40-yard dash record|last=Clark|first=Nate|date=2019-02-02|website=OlympicTalk|language=en|access-date=2019-09-28}}</ref><br>
In May 2019, Bolt spoke in Paris at the [[Viva Technology]] conference, where he introduced the company's future release of the ''Nano'' minicar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/17/usain-bolt-launches-two-seater-electric-vehicle-which-starts-at-9999.html|title=Usain Bolt launches two-seater electric vehicle which starts at $9,999|first=Anmar|last=Frangoul|date=17 May 2019|website=CNBC}}</ref> He also met with French president [[Emmanuel Macron]] while at the conference. While in France, Bolt participated in a CNN interview where he revealed his reasons for founding the company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/business/2019/05/15/usain-bolt-scooter.cnn-business|title=Why Usain Bolt thinks his e-scooter company will succeed - CNN Video|via=www.cnn.com}}</ref> {{Quote box
 |quote  = "I've been to New York, London, Paris and one thing I've noticed is that we all complain about traffic!"
 |author = Usain Bolt
 |source = ''CNN Interview''
}} Bolt argues that his scooter is different, which allows bag, shopping and mobile phone storage. The scooters have capabilities to reach up to 30 MPH, but are typically capped at 15 MPH depending on city regulation. The company has begun operations in a number of U.S. cities, and plans to expand throughout Europe and Asia.

==Music producer==
In July 2019, Bolt made his debut as a dancehall music producer with the release of the ''Olympe Rosé'' riddim that featured 5 tracks from Jamaican dancehall artistes: [[Dexta Daps]] "Big Moves", Munga Honorable "Weekend", [[Christopher Martin (singer)|Christopher Martin]] "Dweet", [[Ding Dong (reggae musician)|Ding Dong]] "Top A Di Top" and football player turned artist Ricardo "Bibi" Gardner "Mount A Gyal".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8528607/usain-bolt-riddim-track-video|title=Usain Bolt Turns Producer: Watch the Olympic Gold Medalist's Music Video: Premiere|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>

In November 2019, he followed up with another compilation called the 'Immortal Riddim' that included tracks from [[Vybz Kartel]], Masicka, Munga Honorable and Christopher Martin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dancehallmag.com/2019/11/29/music/vybz-kartel-drops-adiadking-from-immortal-riddim.html|title=Vybz Kartel Drops 'ADIADKING' From Immortal Riddim|date=2019-11-29|website=DancehallMag|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dancehallmag.com/2019/12/17/news/usain-bolt-talks-about-his-hot-dancehall-riddim-and-brand-new-building.html|title=Usain Bolt Talks About His Hot Dancehall Riddim And Brand New Building|date=2019-12-18|website=DancehallMag|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>

In early January 2021, Bolt released a single titled ''Living The Dream'' with his childhood friend and manager Nugent 'NJ' Walker.<ref>{{Cite web|last=|first=|date=2021-01-04|title='Living The Dream': Usain Bolt Releases New Single|url=http://radiojamaicanewsonline.com/arts-entertainment/living-the-dream-usain-bolt-releases-new-single|access-date=2021-02-01|website=Radio Jamaica News}}</ref>

